1
00:00:13,780 --> 00:00:17,417
[Indistinct conversations]

2
00:00:17,450 --> 00:00:20,020
Here. Come say hi.

3
00:00:27,195 --> 00:00:27,794
[Woman shivers]

4
00:00:27,828 --> 00:00:30,163
Hurry. It's freezing.

5
00:00:30,198 --> 00:00:32,365
Look! There's Santa!

6
00:00:39,339 --> 00:00:41,341
[Narrating] Christmas was
always different for me.

7
00:00:41,374 --> 00:00:45,713
I'd been an elf at santaville
since I was 5 years old.

8
00:00:45,746 --> 00:00:47,715
I knew the names
of every reindeer,

9
00:00:47,748 --> 00:00:50,551
Could keep it straight
how many lords were leaping

10
00:00:50,584 --> 00:00:54,755
And how many ladies dancing
before I learned arithmetic.

11
00:00:54,787 --> 00:00:57,825
Ok, what'd you get
for Christmas last year?

12
00:00:57,857 --> 00:01:00,060
Too late. What'd you get?

13
00:01:00,060 --> 00:01:02,095
Oh, that's really great.

14
00:01:02,130 --> 00:01:03,164
What'd you get?

15
00:01:03,197 --> 00:01:06,499
- I got...
- Uh-huh. How 'bout you?

16
00:01:07,367 --> 00:01:11,139
[Narrating] I missed out
on slumber parties
and school field trips.

17
00:01:11,171 --> 00:01:15,775
It wasn't so bad at first, but
by the time I was a teenager,

18
00:01:15,809 --> 00:01:19,447
I started to take a slightly
different view of things.

19
00:01:19,479 --> 00:01:20,448
Have a merry Christmas,

20
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:23,151
And we hope to see you again
soon at santaville,

21
00:01:23,184 --> 00:01:24,417
Where every day is Christmas.

22
00:01:24,452 --> 00:01:25,186
Thank you. Merry Christmas.

23
00:01:25,218 --> 00:01:26,820
I'd worked for Santa
for so long,

24
00:01:26,853 --> 00:01:28,855
That Christmas didn't have
much magic anymore.

25
00:01:28,889 --> 00:01:32,760
All I knew was the more
holiday spirit people had,

26
00:01:32,793 --> 00:01:35,363
The more work it meant for me.

27
00:01:35,395 --> 00:01:36,364
Have a merry Christmas,

28
00:01:36,396 --> 00:01:39,767
And we hope to see you again
soon at santaville,

29
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:41,769
Where every day is Christmas.

30
00:01:41,802 --> 00:01:44,437
Thanks.

31
00:01:45,806 --> 00:01:46,707
[Cash register rings]

32
00:01:46,740 --> 00:01:47,708
Have a merry Christmas,

33
00:01:47,741 --> 00:01:50,678
And we hope to see you again
soon at santaville,

34
00:01:50,711 --> 00:01:52,545
Where every day is Christmas.

35
00:01:52,579 --> 00:01:55,183
[Laughter]

36
00:01:55,415 --> 00:01:57,218
Such a dork.

37
00:01:57,251 --> 00:01:58,050
You know, for an elf,

38
00:01:58,084 --> 00:01:59,051
You don't really seem
all that jolly.

39
00:01:59,085 --> 00:02:04,492
Yeah. Well, santaville's open
365 days a year.

40
00:02:04,525 --> 00:02:06,793
You kind of
have to pace yourself

41
00:02:06,827 --> 00:02:08,596
With the whole spirit thing.

42
00:02:08,629 --> 00:02:09,697
I don't know.

43
00:02:09,729 --> 00:02:12,832
Just being around you puts me
in the Christmas spirit.

44
00:02:12,866 --> 00:02:15,802
So what's your real name?

45
00:02:16,536 --> 00:02:17,638
Holly is my real name.

46
00:02:17,671 --> 00:02:20,508
Nice to meet you,
not-so-jolly holly.

47
00:02:20,540 --> 00:02:21,341
Heh heh.

48
00:02:21,375 --> 00:02:23,543
My name's Peter.

49
00:02:27,748 --> 00:02:28,481
Yay!

50
00:02:28,516 --> 00:02:29,650
What's that?

51
00:02:29,683 --> 00:02:32,420
Come on.

52
00:02:32,452 --> 00:02:33,287
[Laughter]

53
00:02:33,321 --> 00:02:34,188
All these guys,

54
00:02:34,222 --> 00:02:38,192
And then this one
very cute reindeer says,

55
00:02:38,226 --> 00:02:41,429
"My name is Randolph."

56
00:02:41,461 --> 00:02:42,230
No!

57
00:02:42,263 --> 00:02:44,464
And I said to myself,
"Randolph...

58
00:02:44,497 --> 00:02:46,767
Does not sound like
a reindeer's name."

59
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:47,701
He makes a great Santa.

60
00:02:47,735 --> 00:02:51,439
He should.
He's been doing it all my life.

61
00:02:51,471 --> 00:02:52,572
Nick's my dad.

62
00:02:52,605 --> 00:02:55,508
You dad's name is Nick?
Seriously,

63
00:02:55,542 --> 00:02:56,777
As in Saint Nick?

64
00:02:56,810 --> 00:02:59,546
And you know
what I changed it to?

65
00:02:59,579 --> 00:03:00,180
Rudolph!

66
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:01,915
That's right.
I changed it to Rudolph.

67
00:03:01,948 --> 00:03:04,518
- I get it.
- And from that moment on...

68
00:03:04,552 --> 00:03:06,286
Nick. Holly.

69
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:07,521
Welcome to my world.

70
00:03:07,555 --> 00:03:10,323
They were all
hangin' out together.

71
00:03:10,357 --> 00:03:11,624
[Laughter]

72
00:03:11,659 --> 00:03:12,792
No, really, I like it.

73
00:03:12,825 --> 00:03:17,597
I guess this would sort of
make you an expert on Christmas.

74
00:03:17,630 --> 00:03:18,898
Yeah. Right.

75
00:03:18,932 --> 00:03:22,270
I see this thing all over
during the holidays,

76
00:03:22,303 --> 00:03:24,238
And, I mean,
I just don't get it.

77
00:03:24,272 --> 00:03:25,538
It's gotta be
the weirdest-looking doll.

78
00:03:25,573 --> 00:03:28,408
It's not a doll.
It's a nutcracker.

79
00:03:28,442 --> 00:03:29,710
You know, from the ballet.

80
00:03:29,743 --> 00:03:30,878
Yeah. F-from the ballet.

81
00:03:30,910 --> 00:03:34,681
You've never heard of
the nutcracker ballet?

82
00:03:34,715 --> 00:03:35,916
Tchaikovsky?

83
00:03:35,948 --> 00:03:37,785
Clara and Fritz?

84
00:03:37,818 --> 00:03:39,353
Herr drosselmeyer?

85
00:03:39,387 --> 00:03:41,521
Never really got ballet.

86
00:03:41,554 --> 00:03:42,990
This isn't just ballet.

87
00:03:43,022 --> 00:03:44,591
It's a great
Christmas tradition.

88
00:03:44,624 --> 00:03:48,961
See, Clara gets the nutcracker
as a gift on Christmas Eve,

89
00:03:48,996 --> 00:03:50,463
And it comes to life

90
00:03:50,498 --> 00:03:52,532
And turns into
this handsome prince,

91
00:03:52,565 --> 00:03:57,470
And he has to rescue her
from the evil mouse king and...

92
00:03:57,505 --> 00:04:00,240
I guess you'd have to see it.

93
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:03,344
I will.

94
00:04:06,979 --> 00:04:09,550
What's this?

95
00:04:09,583 --> 00:04:11,451
I make things.

96
00:04:12,320 --> 00:04:14,488
It's beautiful.

97
00:04:14,521 --> 00:04:16,790
Thank you.

98
00:04:17,558 --> 00:04:18,492
Whoo!

99
00:04:18,525 --> 00:04:19,360
[Laughter]

100
00:04:19,392 --> 00:04:20,192
All right, holly,

101
00:04:20,226 --> 00:04:22,996
I got some great
new customers for you.

102
00:04:23,029 --> 00:04:23,931
Just a second, dad.

103
00:04:23,963 --> 00:04:27,301
Uh, holly,
Santa doesn't have any children.

104
00:04:27,335 --> 00:04:29,337
Santa has elves.

105
00:04:29,370 --> 00:04:30,137
Santa.

106
00:04:30,169 --> 00:04:32,806
Yes. I have
the magic suit on. Ok?

107
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:34,073
Ok.

108
00:04:34,106 --> 00:04:38,077
Hey! Well,
how'd you like it if Santa
bought you one of those?

109
00:04:38,110 --> 00:04:38,812
Yeah!

110
00:04:38,846 --> 00:04:40,948
- Hey, did you see this?
- Yeah!

111
00:04:40,981 --> 00:04:43,616
Did you look under
the Christmas tree?

112
00:04:43,650 --> 00:04:45,453
Have you ever seen a...

113
00:04:45,486 --> 00:04:46,619
- No.
- Oh, Santa!

114
00:04:46,653 --> 00:04:51,559
How would you like it if Santa
brought you one of these?

115
00:04:54,061 --> 00:04:55,996
Holly Crosby's office.

116
00:04:56,028 --> 00:04:58,899
Yeah, I know.
I got stuck behind some guy

117
00:04:58,932 --> 00:05:01,535
Unloading one of those
steroid Christmas trees

118
00:05:01,568 --> 00:05:04,103
Everyone gets
all warm and fuzzy about.

119
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:05,037
Where are you?

120
00:05:05,072 --> 00:05:06,038
I'm here now.

121
00:05:06,073 --> 00:05:08,776
Oh. Good morning, Ms. Crosby.
Merry Christmas.

122
00:05:08,809 --> 00:05:10,477
Here are your mail and messages.

123
00:05:10,510 --> 00:05:12,579
The sample's on your desk,
and Mr. holt is on hold.

124
00:05:12,613 --> 00:05:16,015
[Decoration playing
jingle bells instrumental]

125
00:05:16,749 --> 00:05:18,518
Brenda...

126
00:05:18,951 --> 00:05:20,587
What is this?

127
00:05:20,621 --> 00:05:22,423
What is what?

128
00:05:22,455 --> 00:05:23,523
This stuff...

129
00:05:23,557 --> 00:05:24,757
On your desk.

130
00:05:24,791 --> 00:05:25,592
Oh. It's Christmas.

131
00:05:25,626 --> 00:05:28,829
Yeah. It looks
like frosty exploded.

132
00:05:28,862 --> 00:05:32,065
This is a business, Brenda,
not the north pole.

133
00:05:32,098 --> 00:05:35,735
You mean I can't have
Christmas decorations?

134
00:05:36,703 --> 00:05:37,438
Ok, um...

135
00:05:37,471 --> 00:05:40,040
Let's just
tone it down a bit, ok?

136
00:05:40,072 --> 00:05:43,110
Sure. Ok. Thanks, Ms. Crosby.

137
00:05:43,142 --> 00:05:46,646
[Telephone rings]

138
00:05:46,679 --> 00:05:48,882
Holly Crosby's office.

139
00:05:49,850 --> 00:05:54,422
This new Celtic line tested
through the roof, Mr. holt.

140
00:05:54,455 --> 00:05:57,024
Uh, people love that warm,
handcrafted look,

141
00:05:57,057 --> 00:06:00,360
But at big-box prices,
especially for the holidays.

142
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:03,931
That's true. Christmas is
all about tradition,

143
00:06:03,964 --> 00:06:06,066
Which is what
makes this so perfect.

144
00:06:06,098 --> 00:06:09,102
I mean, people'll hang these up
every year,

145
00:06:09,135 --> 00:06:10,903
Pass them down to their kids.

146
00:06:10,938 --> 00:06:14,374
You're creating
a tradition here.

147
00:06:15,475 --> 00:06:18,546
Y-yes, absolutely.
We can ship in 48 hours.

148
00:06:18,578 --> 00:06:19,480
No problem.

149
00:06:19,512 --> 00:06:23,149
No, thank you, Mr. holt.
Thank you very much.

150
00:06:23,183 --> 00:06:25,818
And, uh, merry Christmas
to you, too.

151
00:06:25,852 --> 00:06:28,020
Guess who just doubled
her sales for the month.

152
00:06:28,055 --> 00:06:30,624
Kudos, holly. Well done.
I don't know what it is.

153
00:06:30,657 --> 00:06:33,661
There's just somethin' about
this time of year

154
00:06:33,693 --> 00:06:35,828
That makes you
go into overdrive.

155
00:06:35,862 --> 00:06:36,930
Thank you, Mr. Jennings.

156
00:06:36,964 --> 00:06:39,799
Though it wouldn't hurt
to give your holiday spirit

157
00:06:39,832 --> 00:06:42,570
Just a little smidgeon
of spit-shine.

158
00:06:42,603 --> 00:06:43,604
What do you mean?

159
00:06:43,636 --> 00:06:45,573
Christmas is
a happy time, holly.

160
00:06:45,606 --> 00:06:47,541
You make it sound
like a root canal.

161
00:06:47,575 --> 00:06:49,742
Believe me, I know
what a happy time this is.

162
00:06:49,776 --> 00:06:53,646
We do half our annual sales
in just 6 weeks.

163
00:06:58,686 --> 00:07:01,488
I've been looking over
your schedule for December.

164
00:07:01,522 --> 00:07:04,992
Looks to me like you're planning
on working 12-hour days

165
00:07:05,024 --> 00:07:06,126
Right through
the 12 days of Christmas.

166
00:07:06,158 --> 00:07:09,028
We're so busy right now,
all these last-minute orders.

167
00:07:09,061 --> 00:07:12,131
I have to finalize the photos
for the new catalog.

168
00:07:12,165 --> 00:07:13,233
But when you stay late,

169
00:07:13,266 --> 00:07:15,235
Your whole staff
has to be here, too,

170
00:07:15,268 --> 00:07:17,870
And this time of year,
a little bird tells me

171
00:07:17,904 --> 00:07:20,007
That they'd rather be home
with their families

172
00:07:20,040 --> 00:07:23,511
Or out spreading Christmas
cheer with their friends.

173
00:07:24,244 --> 00:07:25,546
Oh.

174
00:07:25,578 --> 00:07:27,548
Well, no, i... i understand.

175
00:07:27,580 --> 00:07:28,715
Glad to hear it.

176
00:07:28,749 --> 00:07:30,751
So for everyone's sake,

177
00:07:30,783 --> 00:07:33,020
Go home early once in a while.

178
00:07:33,053 --> 00:07:35,656
Put up a tree.
Sip some eggnog.

179
00:07:35,688 --> 00:07:36,923
Write Santa a letter.

180
00:07:36,957 --> 00:07:40,192
Tell him what a good
little sales manager
you've been this year.

181
00:07:40,227 --> 00:07:41,894
Santa and I are like this.

182
00:07:41,928 --> 00:07:45,197
He knows I'm way too busy
for that stuff.

183
00:07:45,232 --> 00:07:45,999
Holly...

184
00:07:46,033 --> 00:07:49,670
You can't be too busy
for Christmas.

185
00:07:49,702 --> 00:07:53,106
[Joy to the world playing]

186
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:04,250
I mean it, honey.
3 years is way too long.

187
00:08:04,283 --> 00:08:05,217
We all miss you.

188
00:08:05,252 --> 00:08:06,253
I wish I could, dad,

189
00:08:06,285 --> 00:08:09,155
But we launch a new line
the first week of January.

190
00:08:09,188 --> 00:08:12,560
It's huge. There's no way
I can take time off.

191
00:08:12,592 --> 00:08:13,326
I understand.

192
00:08:13,360 --> 00:08:14,995
You must be doin'
a heck of a job.

193
00:08:15,027 --> 00:08:17,897
I just wish you didn't
have to be so far away.

194
00:08:17,930 --> 00:08:21,101
Well, you could come
to Boston.

195
00:08:21,133 --> 00:08:25,038
It is my understanding
that trains go both ways.

196
00:08:25,072 --> 00:08:28,542
Yeah. Well, I guess that's
somethin' we have in common,

197
00:08:28,576 --> 00:08:30,010
'Cause santaville
never closes either,

198
00:08:30,043 --> 00:08:32,979
So I can never leave.
What would the kids say?

199
00:08:33,013 --> 00:08:36,883
Um, maybe that Santa's
visiting his daughter.

200
00:08:36,916 --> 00:08:39,787
Honey, you know Santa
doesn't have any children.

201
00:08:39,819 --> 00:08:42,189
Oh. Right. Santa has elves.

202
00:08:42,222 --> 00:08:45,158
That's right,
and you're his number one.

203
00:08:45,192 --> 00:08:48,228
Always have been,
and you always will be.

204
00:08:48,260 --> 00:08:51,263
Ok. Look, dad, I better go.

205
00:08:51,298 --> 00:08:52,199
All right.

206
00:08:52,232 --> 00:08:55,636
Hey, merry Christmas.

207
00:08:56,737 --> 00:08:58,606
You, too.

208
00:08:58,639 --> 00:09:00,207
Night, dad.

209
00:09:26,166 --> 00:09:28,701
[Train whistle blows]

210
00:09:32,038 --> 00:09:33,305
[Train whistle blows]

211
00:09:33,340 --> 00:09:35,776
And a DVD player... blu-ray...

212
00:09:35,808 --> 00:09:37,244
And an omegatron 6000

213
00:09:37,277 --> 00:09:40,614
With all 5 levels and
multiplayer access screen.

214
00:09:40,648 --> 00:09:42,349
You can get that, right?

215
00:09:42,381 --> 00:09:44,084
Um...

216
00:09:44,351 --> 00:09:47,019
Yes. Yes. It's on my list.

217
00:09:47,053 --> 00:09:47,920
Is there anything else?

218
00:09:47,954 --> 00:09:50,157
A zeon command cube,
but it's gotta have

219
00:09:50,190 --> 00:09:52,292
The shuffle feature
for all 83 games,

220
00:09:52,324 --> 00:09:53,392
Or I don't want it.

221
00:09:53,425 --> 00:09:56,395
Games. Oh. I love games.

222
00:09:56,428 --> 00:09:57,197
Games are great,

223
00:09:57,230 --> 00:10:00,600
And I picture you
as a checkers man.

224
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:01,868
Am I right?

225
00:10:01,902 --> 00:10:02,736
What's checkers?

226
00:10:02,769 --> 00:10:04,872
Everybody knows
how to play checkers.

227
00:10:04,904 --> 00:10:06,974
It's a game of the mind.

228
00:10:07,007 --> 00:10:08,108
Sounds lame.

229
00:10:08,141 --> 00:10:09,076
So how does this work?

230
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:11,979
You make the games here
or at the north pole?

231
00:10:12,012 --> 00:10:14,046
That's a very good question,
Willy.

232
00:10:14,081 --> 00:10:17,249
Actually we...
We make the games offsite.

233
00:10:17,284 --> 00:10:19,219
Outsourcing.

234
00:10:19,251 --> 00:10:19,987
Smart.

235
00:10:20,019 --> 00:10:22,990
You know, Willy...

236
00:10:23,255 --> 00:10:28,228
Christmas is... is not just about
multiplayers and Megatrons.

237
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:33,767
Christmas is a magical time
where wonderful things happen,

238
00:10:33,801 --> 00:10:36,770
Things that you'd never expect.

239
00:10:36,804 --> 00:10:39,272
Yeah?

240
00:10:40,708 --> 00:10:42,275
All right, Willy.

241
00:10:42,309 --> 00:10:43,210
Get ready, son,

242
00:10:43,243 --> 00:10:47,379
Because this right here
is Santa's workshop.

243
00:10:47,414 --> 00:10:49,750
Ferocious, huh?

244
00:10:51,017 --> 00:10:52,384
You're kidding, right?

245
00:10:52,419 --> 00:10:54,254
You don't like it?

246
00:10:54,287 --> 00:10:56,189
It's fake.

247
00:10:57,290 --> 00:10:58,958
It's pretend.

248
00:10:58,991 --> 00:11:02,129
Yeah. Y-yeah.

249
00:11:02,162 --> 00:11:03,396
Ferocious, huh?

250
00:11:03,429 --> 00:11:04,096
Heh.

251
00:11:04,131 --> 00:11:05,264
Of course Santa can't show you

252
00:11:05,298 --> 00:11:08,435
How he really makes the toys.
That'd be against the rules.

253
00:11:08,467 --> 00:11:11,337
This is just to help you use
your imagination.

254
00:11:11,370 --> 00:11:12,371
Who are you?

255
00:11:12,405 --> 00:11:16,108
Why, this is one of my elves.
His name is Peter.

256
00:11:16,143 --> 00:11:17,076
You're not really an elf.

257
00:11:17,109 --> 00:11:20,379
I help Santa keep things
running around here.

258
00:11:20,413 --> 00:11:22,249
What else could I be?

259
00:11:22,282 --> 00:11:23,816
Hey, guys, uh, can...

260
00:11:23,851 --> 00:11:25,786
- Uup!
- Who was that?

261
00:11:25,818 --> 00:11:26,419
Who was who?

262
00:11:26,452 --> 00:11:27,153
- I didn't...
- No.

263
00:11:27,187 --> 00:11:28,722
- I didn't see anything.
- No.

264
00:11:28,756 --> 00:11:30,924
Mom, I wanna go back
to the mall.

265
00:11:30,957 --> 00:11:33,092
Well, you guys come back
this weekend,

266
00:11:33,125 --> 00:11:36,263
'Cause we've got
the reindeer races.

267
00:11:37,364 --> 00:11:39,065
I don't get it, Pete.

268
00:11:39,098 --> 00:11:42,235
Kids used to love
Santa's workshop.

269
00:11:42,269 --> 00:11:43,771
Kids have changed.

270
00:11:43,804 --> 00:11:45,806
Santa's workshop has not.

271
00:11:45,839 --> 00:11:47,240
I know.

272
00:11:47,274 --> 00:11:48,241
That's my point.

273
00:11:48,275 --> 00:11:50,210
Earl. Earl!

274
00:11:50,243 --> 00:11:51,311
Sorry, Nick. So sorry.

275
00:11:51,344 --> 00:11:53,213
Earl, let me
tell you something.

276
00:11:53,246 --> 00:11:55,348
That boy sees 2 santas
in the same place,

277
00:11:55,382 --> 00:11:58,919
I mean, that's... that's against
the laws of the universe.

278
00:11:58,951 --> 00:11:59,787
Well...

279
00:11:59,820 --> 00:12:00,720
That could scar him for life.
I just...

280
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:02,856
There's never
anyone here anymore,

281
00:12:02,889 --> 00:12:05,324
And... and I didn't
think about it.

282
00:12:05,358 --> 00:12:06,826
How's it goin', Pete?

283
00:12:06,860 --> 00:12:08,361
Good, Earl. Uh...

284
00:12:08,394 --> 00:12:09,929
Mall, uh, busy today?

285
00:12:09,963 --> 00:12:11,098
A zoo.

286
00:12:11,131 --> 00:12:14,467
You know they turn the heat up
to 80 degrees in that place?

287
00:12:14,500 --> 00:12:16,970
Th-they think it makes people
spend more.

288
00:12:17,003 --> 00:12:18,105
Well, how are they gonna feel

289
00:12:18,137 --> 00:12:20,372
When Santa passes out
from heatstroke?

290
00:12:20,407 --> 00:12:21,941
- Not good.
- Not good. Not good.

291
00:12:21,975 --> 00:12:25,377
Listen, Earl, you should go back
to practicing law.

292
00:12:25,412 --> 00:12:27,247
Really. Come on.

293
00:12:28,447 --> 00:12:30,449
You need a cup of hot cocoa.

294
00:12:30,483 --> 00:12:31,785
Cocoa? I'm burnin' up.

295
00:12:31,819 --> 00:12:34,421
And a piece
of Ginny's pumpkin pie.

296
00:12:34,454 --> 00:12:35,322
Twist my arm.

297
00:12:35,355 --> 00:12:37,290
Don't tempt me.

298
00:12:42,128 --> 00:12:45,532
[Slides clicking]

299
00:12:49,402 --> 00:12:52,238
[Passing siren]

300
00:12:55,943 --> 00:12:58,177
So what do you hear
from holly?

301
00:12:58,210 --> 00:13:00,380
She's doin' well,
loves her job.

302
00:13:00,413 --> 00:13:02,949
Course, this is
a busy time of year,

303
00:13:02,983 --> 00:13:05,384
So she can't come home
for Christmas.

304
00:13:05,418 --> 00:13:07,086
She says that every year.

305
00:13:07,120 --> 00:13:10,090
Earl, she has
an important job.

306
00:13:10,123 --> 00:13:11,358
People depend on her,

307
00:13:11,390 --> 00:13:14,994
Kind of like kids depend on me,
you know?

308
00:13:15,028 --> 00:13:17,097
I don't know about that.

309
00:13:17,129 --> 00:13:18,331
Don't start.

310
00:13:18,365 --> 00:13:20,167
Start what?

311
00:13:21,500 --> 00:13:24,337
All I'm sayin'
is that in our day,

312
00:13:24,371 --> 00:13:26,438
It was a baseball mitt
or a kite

313
00:13:26,473 --> 00:13:31,044
Or maybe an electric train
if you were lucky.

314
00:13:46,292 --> 00:13:49,462
Both: Moonlight and mistletoe.

315
00:13:56,503 --> 00:13:59,006
What are you
mumblin' about over there?

316
00:13:59,039 --> 00:14:00,239
You know what I'm gonna do?

317
00:14:00,272 --> 00:14:02,409
I think I'm gonna get the sleigh
out and give Ginny a ride home

318
00:14:02,442 --> 00:14:04,411
And thank her
for makin' the pie for us.

319
00:14:04,444 --> 00:14:06,012
Heh. Hey, Romeo,

320
00:14:06,046 --> 00:14:08,447
She's been comin' on to you
for 5 years,

321
00:14:08,481 --> 00:14:11,084
And you haven't given her
the time of day.

322
00:14:11,117 --> 00:14:14,254
Earl, I'm not givin' her
the time of day, ok?

323
00:14:14,286 --> 00:14:17,390
I'm just givin' her
a simple sleigh ride home

324
00:14:17,424 --> 00:14:19,960
Under the moonlight with me...

325
00:14:20,559 --> 00:14:22,561
You're jealous.

326
00:14:35,607 --> 00:14:36,443
Whoa.

327
00:14:36,476 --> 00:14:39,012
[Horse neighs]

328
00:14:39,046 --> 00:14:40,413
[Laughs]

329
00:14:40,447 --> 00:14:41,915
Evenin', Ginny.

330
00:14:41,949 --> 00:14:42,882
So what's all this?

331
00:14:42,916 --> 00:14:45,518
Well, I thought
you might want a lift home.

332
00:14:45,552 --> 00:14:49,589
I got you a blanket,
some hot cider to keep you warm,

333
00:14:49,621 --> 00:14:52,525
And of course I brought
my favorite reindeer.

334
00:14:52,559 --> 00:14:54,427
You do know that's a horse.

335
00:14:54,461 --> 00:14:56,463
Well, I know
he looks like a horse right now,

336
00:14:56,496 --> 00:14:58,297
But once the Christmas magic
kicks in,

337
00:14:58,330 --> 00:15:00,900
His inner reindeer comes out.

338
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:03,636
You think
he can pull us both?

339
00:15:03,669 --> 00:15:06,273
Well, dasher's lost
a little bit of his dash

340
00:15:06,306 --> 00:15:09,675
Over the years, but one tug
of these reins, and off...

341
00:15:09,709 --> 00:15:10,576
- [grunts]
- Whoa!

342
00:15:10,609 --> 00:15:11,510
- Hey!
- Oh, whoa! Whoa!

343
00:15:11,543 --> 00:15:14,180
- You forgot something!
- Whoa! Oh! No! Oh!

344
00:15:14,214 --> 00:15:16,682
- Nick?
- The tree. Please. No, no, no!

345
00:15:16,716 --> 00:15:18,285
Look out! The tree!

346
00:15:18,317 --> 00:15:19,586
I know! I know!

347
00:15:19,618 --> 00:15:21,387
Ohh. Ohh.

348
00:15:21,421 --> 00:15:24,291
- Nick!
- [Gasps] I'm fine. I'm fine.

349
00:15:24,323 --> 00:15:25,624
Nick!

350
00:15:27,594 --> 00:15:31,464
Green Mountain train 57
arriving from Boston.

351
00:15:31,498 --> 00:15:36,036
Green Mountain train 57
arriving from Boston.

352
00:15:36,768 --> 00:15:37,836
That's fine, Brenda.

353
00:15:37,869 --> 00:15:39,706
Just call me the minute
the purchase order gets there.

354
00:15:39,738 --> 00:15:41,407
- Any time?
- Absolutely. Day or night.

355
00:15:41,441 --> 00:15:42,374
Ms. Crosby, Peter lowdell.

356
00:15:42,408 --> 00:15:43,543
Even if that means
missing my choir practice?

357
00:15:43,576 --> 00:15:46,245
No, Brenda, I don't mean
for you to miss choir practice.

358
00:15:46,278 --> 00:15:47,379
I know you have a solo.

359
00:15:47,413 --> 00:15:48,215
- Clear out.
- I just meant...

360
00:15:48,247 --> 00:15:50,050
I'll do it if you want,
Ms. Crosby.

361
00:15:50,083 --> 00:15:52,284
Look, just call me, ok?
I have to go.

362
00:15:52,318 --> 00:15:54,286
[Sighs] Hi. Sorry. Business.

363
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:56,322
- No problem.
- How's my father? Is he ok?

364
00:15:56,355 --> 00:15:57,557
Oh, sure. Yeah. He's fine.

365
00:15:57,590 --> 00:15:59,258
Listen, I have my truck
parked right over here.

366
00:15:59,291 --> 00:16:00,960
I'm still not exactly clear
on what happened.

367
00:16:00,960 --> 00:16:02,429
How did he get hurt?

368
00:16:02,462 --> 00:16:03,996
Doctor said it
was the worst

369
00:16:04,031 --> 00:16:05,332
Sleighing accident
he's ever seen.

370
00:16:05,365 --> 00:16:06,366
Of course, he said it was

371
00:16:06,398 --> 00:16:09,568
The only sleighing accident
he's ever seen, so...

372
00:16:09,601 --> 00:16:11,471
Actually there were
34 sleighing accidents

373
00:16:11,503 --> 00:16:15,208
In new england just last year.
It's not funny.

374
00:16:15,241 --> 00:16:16,508
Right. Very serious.

375
00:16:16,543 --> 00:16:19,445
Driving a sleigh
in the middle of the night,

376
00:16:19,479 --> 00:16:20,246
That is so typical.

377
00:16:20,280 --> 00:16:21,413
He's lucky
he didn't break his neck.

378
00:16:21,447 --> 00:16:25,285
Uh, I think it would take more
than a head-on with a tree

379
00:16:25,317 --> 00:16:26,118
To keep your dad down.

380
00:16:26,153 --> 00:16:27,419
Busted up his leg
pretty good, though.

381
00:16:27,453 --> 00:16:30,456
Won't be driving anything
for a while.

382
00:16:30,490 --> 00:16:34,460
How l... did the doctor say how
long he'd be in the hospital?

383
00:16:34,494 --> 00:16:35,262
Oh, he's home.

384
00:16:35,294 --> 00:16:38,198
Home? It hasn't
even been 2 days.

385
00:16:38,230 --> 00:16:41,134
You ever try to keep Nick
somewhere he didn't wanna be?

386
00:16:41,168 --> 00:16:42,301
Point taken.

387
00:16:42,334 --> 00:16:46,106
Don't worry, though. I've been
takin' good care of him...

388
00:16:46,139 --> 00:16:47,439
Me, Ginny, Earl.

389
00:16:47,473 --> 00:16:50,277
Sounds like he doesn't
even really need me here.

390
00:16:50,309 --> 00:16:53,445
Are you kidding? That's all
he's been talking about.

391
00:16:53,479 --> 00:16:56,315
Oh. Good.

392
00:17:00,287 --> 00:17:02,622
Nick says you like it
in the city.

393
00:17:02,655 --> 00:17:03,422
Uh-huh.

394
00:17:03,455 --> 00:17:05,392
Must keep you
pretty busy, though,

395
00:17:05,425 --> 00:17:08,827
Work and all.
He sure misses you.

396
00:17:08,861 --> 00:17:10,696
I'm sorry.
What was your name?

397
00:17:10,729 --> 00:17:13,100
Peter. Peter. Peter lowdell.
It's ok.

398
00:17:13,132 --> 00:17:14,133
Oh. Peter. Right.

399
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:16,369
Peter, do you work
for my father?

400
00:17:16,403 --> 00:17:17,736
I used to be on the payroll.

401
00:17:17,770 --> 00:17:19,738
Now I'm more
what you call a volunteer.

402
00:17:19,772 --> 00:17:22,409
Pick up odd jobs
around town, though,

403
00:17:22,441 --> 00:17:25,578
Paint signs for the locals,
that kind of thing.

404
00:17:25,612 --> 00:17:28,514
Mainly I like Nick.
I like it here.

405
00:17:28,548 --> 00:17:30,650
It's a nice place.

406
00:17:31,284 --> 00:17:33,153
Right.

407
00:17:36,388 --> 00:17:39,326
Green Mountain number 57
departing Chester

408
00:17:39,358 --> 00:17:43,130
For white river junction.
All aboard.

409
00:17:49,702 --> 00:17:52,272
You don't remember me, do you?

410
00:17:52,304 --> 00:17:54,207
Should I?

411
00:17:54,241 --> 00:17:56,176
I don't know.

412
00:17:56,209 --> 00:17:58,377
We talked about the ballet once.

413
00:17:58,410 --> 00:18:00,479
Sorry.

414
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:03,583
Long time ago.

415
00:18:18,631 --> 00:18:20,167
Wow. The inn look deserted.

416
00:18:20,200 --> 00:18:22,169
They don't serve lunches
anymore.

417
00:18:22,202 --> 00:18:23,502
Business was too slow.

418
00:18:23,535 --> 00:18:25,504
Dinner's only on the weekends.

419
00:18:25,537 --> 00:18:26,572
You're kidding.

420
00:18:26,606 --> 00:18:29,875
Wow. That place was always
packed this time of year.

421
00:18:29,909 --> 00:18:33,680
Families never missed
celebrating Christmas.

422
00:18:40,519 --> 00:18:42,554
There she is!

423
00:18:42,588 --> 00:18:43,623
Dad! Oh, my God!

424
00:18:43,656 --> 00:18:45,625
Oh, I'm sorry you had to come
all this way, honey.

425
00:18:45,658 --> 00:18:48,594
- Oh, no. Stop. A-are you ok?
- Oh, I'm fine.

426
00:18:48,628 --> 00:18:49,928
You didn't tell me
he was in a wheelchair.

427
00:18:49,961 --> 00:18:52,165
Oh, I'm not in a wheelchair.
I mean,

428
00:18:52,199 --> 00:18:54,433
I'm in a wheelchair, but I can
get around great on crutches.

429
00:18:54,466 --> 00:18:55,802
- No, you can't.
- Mind your own business.

430
00:18:55,835 --> 00:18:59,639
You know, I should
be really angry at you.
What were you thinking?

431
00:18:59,672 --> 00:19:04,576
Well, I'd been thinking about
enterin' dasher in the derby.

432
00:19:05,377 --> 00:19:06,245
Dad...

433
00:19:06,279 --> 00:19:08,314
Dasher is 20 years old.
Neither one of you

434
00:19:08,348 --> 00:19:09,649
Has any business
riding around in a sleigh.

435
00:19:09,681 --> 00:19:13,319
Don't you start, too.
I've been gettin' it
from all sides, honey.

436
00:19:13,352 --> 00:19:14,253
Good. You deserve it.

437
00:19:14,286 --> 00:19:17,224
- That's what I told him.
- [Clears throat]

438
00:19:17,257 --> 00:19:19,726
Listen, it's just great
havin' you back here.

439
00:19:19,759 --> 00:19:20,727
Now we can get started.

440
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:23,429
- Well, dad, i...
- I've even hung the mistletoe.

441
00:19:23,463 --> 00:19:24,430
You just worry
about getting better.

442
00:19:24,464 --> 00:19:27,866
Hey, I'm not worried
about anything, honey,

443
00:19:27,900 --> 00:19:29,000
Not with you back.

444
00:19:29,035 --> 00:19:32,239
It's gonna be like old times,
holly home for Christmas.

445
00:19:32,272 --> 00:19:33,240
Who's hungry?

446
00:19:33,273 --> 00:19:34,241
Speaking of which,

447
00:19:34,274 --> 00:19:36,343
I was thinking about
your pot roast this morning.

448
00:19:36,376 --> 00:19:37,777
Oh, you should taste it, Peter.

449
00:19:37,810 --> 00:19:40,979
She makes it with,
uh, carrots and potatoes,
a-and she has a light sauce.

450
00:19:41,012 --> 00:19:41,881
Can't wait.

451
00:19:41,913 --> 00:19:43,716
It's not bland
like your Turkey meatloaf.

452
00:19:43,750 --> 00:19:44,650
You like my Turkey meatloaf.

453
00:19:44,684 --> 00:19:46,286
I hate your Turkey meatloaf.
It's terrible.

454
00:19:46,319 --> 00:19:47,486
You always eat it.
You've never complained.

455
00:19:47,519 --> 00:19:48,255
You... you put ketchup
and mustard and all...

456
00:19:48,288 --> 00:19:49,389
No, that's all
that you give me.

457
00:19:49,421 --> 00:19:51,590
I-I've been tryin' to humor you
by makin' you feel good.

458
00:19:51,623 --> 00:19:53,460
- You know what'd make me feel...
- Ok!

459
00:19:53,492 --> 00:19:55,427
I'll make the pot roast.

460
00:19:55,462 --> 00:19:57,929
[Sighs]

461
00:20:04,437 --> 00:20:07,474
Well, he's got a pot
for the pot roast.

462
00:20:07,506 --> 00:20:11,377
That's about it.
Have to go to the grocery store.

463
00:20:11,410 --> 00:20:12,644
Still pacing yourself?

464
00:20:12,679 --> 00:20:14,380
Excuse me?

465
00:20:14,413 --> 00:20:15,981
That's how you phrased it.

466
00:20:16,015 --> 00:20:18,984
365 days a year,
you have to pace yourself

467
00:20:19,018 --> 00:20:22,255
With this whole
Christmas spirit thing.

468
00:20:22,789 --> 00:20:24,957
We have met before.

469
00:20:25,825 --> 00:20:27,894
You should tell him.

470
00:20:28,528 --> 00:20:29,495
What? Tell who?

471
00:20:29,529 --> 00:20:32,364
That you're not staying
for Christmas. He's...

472
00:20:32,399 --> 00:20:34,000
He's getting his hopes up.

473
00:20:34,032 --> 00:20:38,470
I'm sorry. Exactly when did
I invite you to discuss my...

474
00:20:38,505 --> 00:20:40,440
[Cellphone rings]

475
00:20:40,472 --> 00:20:41,707
[Ring]

476
00:20:41,741 --> 00:20:42,641
Here.

477
00:20:42,674 --> 00:20:46,313
You can borrow my truck
to go to the market.

478
00:20:46,346 --> 00:20:46,978
[Ring]

479
00:20:47,013 --> 00:20:49,382
You should probably get that.

480
00:20:49,416 --> 00:20:50,016
[Ring]

481
00:20:50,048 --> 00:20:50,982
Yeah, Brenda?

482
00:20:51,017 --> 00:20:53,051
Mr. holt's Celtic line
is ready for shipping.

483
00:20:53,084 --> 00:20:56,423
Yes. Yes.
Have them shipped right away.

484
00:21:13,340 --> 00:21:14,373
Holly?

485
00:21:14,406 --> 00:21:16,041
Holly Crosby?

486
00:21:16,075 --> 00:21:18,845
It's della, della Wallace.

487
00:21:18,878 --> 00:21:20,412
Well, Wallace now.

488
00:21:20,447 --> 00:21:21,881
Della Hamilton from high school.

489
00:21:21,913 --> 00:21:23,450
Oh. Della.

490
00:21:23,482 --> 00:21:26,953
Wow. I-it's been forever.
I can't believe it.

491
00:21:26,985 --> 00:21:27,753
I know.

492
00:21:27,787 --> 00:21:29,456
Oh, you look fabulous.

493
00:21:29,488 --> 00:21:33,725
I almost didn't recognize you
without your little elf suit.

494
00:21:33,759 --> 00:21:35,727
Yeah, my claim to fame.

495
00:21:35,761 --> 00:21:38,431
With the little pompom
on your hat.

496
00:21:38,465 --> 00:21:39,531
Quite the fashion statement.

497
00:21:39,566 --> 00:21:41,600
Yeah, and all that red.
I used to say

498
00:21:41,633 --> 00:21:43,903
I could see you coming
a mile away.

499
00:21:43,936 --> 00:21:45,372
I remember.

500
00:21:45,405 --> 00:21:47,606
Oh, it's so good to see you.

501
00:21:47,639 --> 00:21:50,410
How's your dad? Is he ok?

502
00:21:50,443 --> 00:21:51,378
Yeah, ok enough to want me

503
00:21:51,411 --> 00:21:54,013
To cook this pot roast
I haven't made in years.

504
00:21:54,045 --> 00:21:57,384
Yeah, it's always something.
My family's the same way.

505
00:21:57,417 --> 00:21:58,918
Oh, you have a family.
That's... that's great.

506
00:21:58,951 --> 00:22:03,556
Yeah, living the glamorous life
of the soccer mom and loving it.

507
00:22:03,589 --> 00:22:06,359
Roger and I have 3 boys now.

508
00:22:06,393 --> 00:22:06,925
Roger...

509
00:22:06,959 --> 00:22:08,126
Oh, Roger Wallace.

510
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:09,095
Oh, you remember.

511
00:22:09,127 --> 00:22:12,598
Used to read the announcements
in high school.

512
00:22:12,632 --> 00:22:15,835
Oh, yeah. Right.
Roger, with all the...

513
00:22:15,867 --> 00:22:17,669
Oh, that was just an allergy.

514
00:22:17,704 --> 00:22:19,971
His face cleared right up
in college.

515
00:22:20,006 --> 00:22:22,409
He's got his own lumberyard now.

516
00:22:22,442 --> 00:22:24,076
Wow. No kiddin'?

517
00:22:24,109 --> 00:22:25,110
Yeah.

518
00:22:25,144 --> 00:22:28,614
So, are you seeing anybody?

519
00:22:29,516 --> 00:22:30,883
Me? No.

520
00:22:30,917 --> 00:22:32,952
No. Who's got the time?

521
00:22:32,984 --> 00:22:33,953
Uh, you know what?

522
00:22:33,986 --> 00:22:36,423
The three of us
should get together for coffee.

523
00:22:36,456 --> 00:22:39,526
- Oh, I don't know.
- Oh, oh, don't be silly.

524
00:22:39,559 --> 00:22:42,995
We'll meet you at the inn
tomorrow. 4:00?

525
00:22:43,029 --> 00:22:44,763
How does that sound?

526
00:22:44,796 --> 00:22:46,698
Yeah. Ok. That sounds great.

527
00:22:46,732 --> 00:22:49,068
- Great. It's a date.
- All right.

528
00:22:49,100 --> 00:22:51,037
[Sighs] It seems so long ago.

529
00:22:51,070 --> 00:22:53,440
I mean, I know
it was different for you,

530
00:22:53,473 --> 00:22:54,673
'Cause you had to be there,

531
00:22:54,706 --> 00:22:58,511
But for the rest of us,
it was so special.

532
00:22:58,545 --> 00:23:01,380
I mean, we never missed
a tree lighting ceremony,

533
00:23:01,380 --> 00:23:04,816
And we looked so forward
to the holidays at santaville.

534
00:23:04,851 --> 00:23:07,654
Now it seems nobody
finds the time anymore.

535
00:23:07,686 --> 00:23:11,123
It's kind of sad, isn't it?

536
00:23:11,156 --> 00:23:12,658
Yeah.

537
00:23:12,692 --> 00:23:13,860
Yeah.

538
00:23:13,893 --> 00:23:16,763
Well, I'll see you tomorrow.

539
00:23:16,796 --> 00:23:19,065
Ok. Bye.

540
00:23:20,767 --> 00:23:25,837
Mmm. Peter, was that not
the star on the top of the tree?

541
00:23:25,871 --> 00:23:26,538
That was good.

542
00:23:26,573 --> 00:23:28,708
It was good? It was wonderful.

543
00:23:28,740 --> 00:23:30,209
It was wonderful, holly.

544
00:23:30,241 --> 00:23:31,511
Thanks, dad.

545
00:23:31,543 --> 00:23:33,712
Which reminds me,
we should save a little
somethin' for Earl,

546
00:23:33,745 --> 00:23:36,182
'Cause he's gonna stop by
after his shift.

547
00:23:36,214 --> 00:23:36,949
How is Earl?

548
00:23:36,983 --> 00:23:37,849
He's doin' well.
He's doin' well.

549
00:23:37,883 --> 00:23:40,218
He's just, uh,
not lawyerin' much anymore,

550
00:23:40,251 --> 00:23:42,188
'Cause he's doin'
double Santa duty,

551
00:23:42,220 --> 00:23:45,558
For us and the mall,
so he's kinda lost interest.

552
00:23:45,592 --> 00:23:46,892
Which is why it's wonderful

553
00:23:46,926 --> 00:23:50,530
That I'm gonna have you around
to help out.

554
00:23:50,563 --> 00:23:51,564
Yeah, dad, about that...

555
00:23:51,598 --> 00:23:55,468
Here. You know,
let me clear some of this away.

556
00:23:55,502 --> 00:23:56,636
Mm-hmm.

557
00:23:57,069 --> 00:24:01,440
Dad, I came because I wanted
to make sure that you were ok.

558
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:04,476
I appreciate that, honey.
I really do.

559
00:24:04,511 --> 00:24:05,478
But I can't stay.

560
00:24:05,512 --> 00:24:07,847
Well, I didn't think
you were movin' back home.

561
00:24:07,879 --> 00:24:10,549
I figured you'd leave
right after Christmas.

562
00:24:10,582 --> 00:24:12,083
N...

563
00:24:12,117 --> 00:24:14,720
I'm not staying for Christmas.

564
00:24:14,754 --> 00:24:15,855
What do you mean?

565
00:24:15,887 --> 00:24:17,557
I can stay
for a couple more days,

566
00:24:17,589 --> 00:24:21,193
But I need to get back
to the city, back to my work.

567
00:24:21,226 --> 00:24:22,061
Honey, it's Christmas.

568
00:24:22,093 --> 00:24:23,895
Yeah. I-it's not
about Christmas, dad.

569
00:24:23,929 --> 00:24:26,065
There are people
who depend on me.

570
00:24:26,097 --> 00:24:27,165
I depend on you.

571
00:24:27,199 --> 00:24:28,467
I... i know, and I'll...
I'll do everything that I can.

572
00:24:28,501 --> 00:24:33,139
I'll hire someone to
help you out until you
get back on your feet.

573
00:24:33,171 --> 00:24:36,175
I'm not gonna have
some stranger in my house.

574
00:24:36,207 --> 00:24:38,276
Holly, we're family,

575
00:24:38,309 --> 00:24:40,278
And family
takes care of family.

576
00:24:40,311 --> 00:24:43,516
Nick, I could handle things
around here,

577
00:24:43,550 --> 00:24:44,716
The... with the cooking,
the cleaning.

578
00:24:44,751 --> 00:24:47,554
You hear that?
With him cookin',
I could starve to death.

579
00:24:47,587 --> 00:24:50,557
I'm glad you're home, honey.
But it reminds me

580
00:24:50,590 --> 00:24:52,258
Earl is not gonna
make the Turkey this year.

581
00:24:52,290 --> 00:24:53,092
Holly's here.

582
00:24:53,125 --> 00:24:56,128
- Dad!
- His Turkey's very dry, honey.

583
00:24:56,162 --> 00:24:57,929
Have you
been listening to me?

584
00:24:57,963 --> 00:24:59,865
Yes, honey,
but you're just tired

585
00:24:59,898 --> 00:25:01,500
From the train ride up here,
which reminds me

586
00:25:01,500 --> 00:25:03,268
We'll talk about it
in the morning

587
00:25:03,302 --> 00:25:04,903
When you make
your holiday breakfast.

588
00:25:04,936 --> 00:25:07,707
You're gonna love her scones.

589
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:09,208
[Sighs]

590
00:25:09,240 --> 00:25:12,644
Welcome home, honey,
and merry Christmas.

591
00:25:19,586 --> 00:25:21,588
[Sighs]

592
00:25:24,891 --> 00:25:27,326
[Cellphone rings]

593
00:25:27,358 --> 00:25:28,327
[Ring]

594
00:25:28,359 --> 00:25:29,061
Hello.

595
00:25:29,095 --> 00:25:29,795
- Holly.
- Oh, Mr. Jennings. Hi.

596
00:25:29,829 --> 00:25:30,962
- How's your dad?
- No, he's ok.

597
00:25:30,996 --> 00:25:35,266
I-I'll definitely be in the
office next week, no problem.

598
00:25:35,301 --> 00:25:37,335
Well, then you'll be
the only one.

599
00:25:37,368 --> 00:25:39,270
I'm havin' my skiis waxed
as we speak,

600
00:25:39,305 --> 00:25:43,042
And our clients'll all be
into vacation mode by next week,

601
00:25:43,075 --> 00:25:44,843
Which is what
you should be doing.

602
00:25:44,876 --> 00:25:47,113
Uh, yeah.
I don't need a vacation.

603
00:25:47,146 --> 00:25:48,314
I don't want a vacation.

604
00:25:48,346 --> 00:25:51,584
Which, as I recall,
is exactly what you said

605
00:25:51,618 --> 00:25:54,220
This time last year
and the year before.

606
00:25:54,253 --> 00:25:55,854
Uh, yeah, but I love my work.

607
00:25:55,887 --> 00:25:58,591
There'll be plenty of work
after the holidays.

608
00:25:58,625 --> 00:25:59,958
Meantime, we got you covered.

609
00:25:59,991 --> 00:26:02,961
Look after your dad
and try to enjoy yourself.

610
00:26:02,995 --> 00:26:05,031
Yeah. No, see,
that's the thing. I...

611
00:26:05,064 --> 00:26:07,298
- Give your dad our best.
- No, wait. Mr...

612
00:26:07,333 --> 00:26:08,734
And, holly, merry Christmas.

613
00:26:08,768 --> 00:26:12,038
Wait. No. M-Mr. Jennings.
[Groans]

614
00:26:12,071 --> 00:26:14,807
[Groans]

615
00:26:22,848 --> 00:26:24,316
What?

616
00:26:33,358 --> 00:26:36,295
"Past due." "Urgent."

617
00:26:36,327 --> 00:26:39,030
Dad, what have you been doing?

618
00:26:39,064 --> 00:26:41,868
All these urgent notices,
these bills.

619
00:26:41,900 --> 00:26:44,103
I'm just a little behind,
that's all.

620
00:26:44,136 --> 00:26:45,003
A little behind?

621
00:26:45,036 --> 00:26:47,338
Dad, some of these bills
are 6 months old.

622
00:26:47,373 --> 00:26:49,007
Well, we had
a couple slow years,

623
00:26:49,040 --> 00:26:51,377
A-and I kept up
until my savings ran out.

624
00:26:51,409 --> 00:26:52,844
Why didn't you tell me?

625
00:26:52,879 --> 00:26:54,313
Honey, you have your own life.

626
00:26:54,345 --> 00:26:57,116
I'm not gonna trouble you
with my problems.

627
00:26:57,149 --> 00:26:58,950
Besides, it's December,

628
00:26:58,984 --> 00:27:01,287
And that's always
our best month, remember?

629
00:27:01,320 --> 00:27:03,690
They can come after
your assets, dad.

630
00:27:03,723 --> 00:27:04,923
Do you know what that means?

631
00:27:04,957 --> 00:27:08,027
Who's gonna do
a thing like that to Santa?

632
00:27:08,059 --> 00:27:11,663
These bills
aren't made out to Santa.

633
00:27:11,698 --> 00:27:13,832
They're made out to Nick Crosby.

634
00:27:13,866 --> 00:27:14,701
You always were a worrier.

635
00:27:14,733 --> 00:27:18,036
Honey, you have to have
a little faith.

636
00:27:18,069 --> 00:27:20,071
Wonderful things
can happen at Christmas.

637
00:27:20,105 --> 00:27:23,442
Well, then you better come up
with a real miracle, dad.

638
00:27:23,474 --> 00:27:28,314
Otherwise, this time next year,
there won't be a santaville.

639
00:27:48,267 --> 00:27:50,101
Thank you for seeing me here

640
00:27:50,135 --> 00:27:51,402
On such short notice,
Mr. corwell.

641
00:27:51,437 --> 00:27:55,808
Holly, I just wish
we were meeting under
better circumstances.

642
00:27:55,842 --> 00:27:58,244
Around here,
we all love our Santa.

643
00:27:58,277 --> 00:28:00,246
You've known my father
for 30 years.

644
00:28:00,279 --> 00:28:03,115
This bank loaned him the money
to buy the property,

645
00:28:03,149 --> 00:28:05,284
To renovate the buildings,
to create santaville.

646
00:28:05,317 --> 00:28:08,955
You know the economic impact
he's had on the community,

647
00:28:08,987 --> 00:28:10,722
The tourists he's brought in...

648
00:28:10,757 --> 00:28:11,523
Of course he has.

649
00:28:11,557 --> 00:28:13,259
I used to take my family
every year.

650
00:28:13,291 --> 00:28:16,996
It was a family tradition.
Now my grandkids,

651
00:28:17,029 --> 00:28:19,298
They've got, like, 500 channels.

652
00:28:19,330 --> 00:28:22,834
What do they care
about santaville?

653
00:28:22,869 --> 00:28:24,270
All the time
and love my father

654
00:28:24,303 --> 00:28:27,940
Has put into this town,
that has to mean something.

655
00:28:27,973 --> 00:28:28,907
Yes, it does.

656
00:28:28,941 --> 00:28:29,942
It means the world

657
00:28:29,975 --> 00:28:33,379
To anyone who remembers
what santaville once was.

658
00:28:33,411 --> 00:28:34,445
But it's still there.

659
00:28:34,480 --> 00:28:36,248
People only drive
through here now

660
00:28:36,282 --> 00:28:39,351
Because we're on the way
to the ski lifts.

661
00:28:39,385 --> 00:28:42,321
We're lucky
if they even stop for gas.

662
00:28:42,354 --> 00:28:45,892
Why would they stop
for santaville?

663
00:28:46,826 --> 00:28:48,126
I'm sorry, holly.

664
00:28:48,159 --> 00:28:52,498
I've already extended
your father more credit
than I should have.

665
00:29:40,279 --> 00:29:41,981
Dad!

666
00:29:56,929 --> 00:29:57,997
Earl, are you here?

667
00:29:58,029 --> 00:29:59,565
Supposed to be out there
on that sleigh.

668
00:29:59,597 --> 00:30:01,800
Have a heart. I'm freezin'
my bells off out there.

669
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:04,270
Besides, haven't had
a visitor since lunch.

670
00:30:04,303 --> 00:30:07,538
Well, kids used to play hooky
just to come here in December.

671
00:30:07,573 --> 00:30:08,406
It's the Internet.

672
00:30:08,440 --> 00:30:10,408
They're sending
virtual Christmas cards

673
00:30:10,441 --> 00:30:12,077
And living virtual lives. Hey!

674
00:30:12,111 --> 00:30:15,513
Ran into John corwell
on my way back from the mall.

675
00:30:15,547 --> 00:30:16,615
Says holly was up to see him.

676
00:30:16,648 --> 00:30:21,086
Yeah. She's takin' care of
a couple of things for me.

677
00:30:21,120 --> 00:30:22,020
What kind of things?

678
00:30:22,054 --> 00:30:25,290
She's takin' care of 'em.
She always does.

679
00:30:25,324 --> 00:30:27,359
Nick...

680
00:30:27,393 --> 00:30:29,395
I been your friend,
your lawyer

681
00:30:29,428 --> 00:30:31,497
Since longer
than I can remember.

682
00:30:31,529 --> 00:30:32,297
Whatever's goin' on,

683
00:30:32,331 --> 00:30:35,633
You know I'll help
in any way I can.

684
00:30:35,666 --> 00:30:37,403
I know that, Earl.

685
00:30:37,436 --> 00:30:41,974
You don't have 50 grand
stuck in that boot, do you?

686
00:30:42,008 --> 00:30:44,309
$50,000?

687
00:30:44,343 --> 00:30:46,277
It's funny how some numbers
will make the hair

688
00:30:46,311 --> 00:30:48,447
On the back of your neck
stand up.

689
00:30:48,480 --> 00:30:50,215
Earl...

690
00:30:50,248 --> 00:30:52,283
Gonna be all right. Don't worry.

691
00:30:52,317 --> 00:30:54,585
Get back out there.

692
00:30:58,057 --> 00:31:01,326
[Clears throat] Ho ho ho!

693
00:31:10,236 --> 00:31:12,271
When I saw that sleigh
upside down

694
00:31:12,303 --> 00:31:14,973
And your dad all catawampus
in the snow,

695
00:31:15,006 --> 00:31:18,410
I'm tellin' you, honey,
my heart stopped.

696
00:31:19,210 --> 00:31:22,114
It was a sweet thought, though.

697
00:31:23,382 --> 00:31:24,984
I'll give him that.

698
00:31:25,016 --> 00:31:26,919
Sleigh ride under a full moon.

699
00:31:26,953 --> 00:31:29,621
Heh. He can be quite the charmer
when he wants to be.

700
00:31:29,654 --> 00:31:32,357
Is there something
I should know about?

701
00:31:32,391 --> 00:31:35,326
Heh. You tell me,
and we'll both know.

702
00:31:35,360 --> 00:31:38,030
He flirts. I flirt back.

703
00:31:38,064 --> 00:31:39,398
Gets us through the day.

704
00:31:39,431 --> 00:31:43,469
Well, thanks for
taking care of him, Ginny.

705
00:31:43,502 --> 00:31:45,404
I know he can be...

706
00:31:45,437 --> 00:31:46,505
Difficult sometimes.

707
00:31:46,538 --> 00:31:51,410
He's not so bad, you know,
once you get used to him.

708
00:31:51,443 --> 00:31:55,047
And he sure has perked up
since you got home, honey.

709
00:31:55,081 --> 00:31:57,416
Sure.

710
00:31:58,383 --> 00:32:01,920
Sweetheart, is there something
that you wanna talk about?

711
00:32:01,920 --> 00:32:04,722
Oh. No, nothing. I'm fine.

712
00:32:04,756 --> 00:32:05,856
I just, um...

713
00:32:05,891 --> 00:32:09,628
You know, I think that my...
My friends are runnin' late.

714
00:32:09,660 --> 00:32:10,429
[Telephone rings]

715
00:32:10,461 --> 00:32:14,166
Well, I'm here
if you ever need me.

716
00:32:14,199 --> 00:32:15,234
Ok?

717
00:32:15,267 --> 00:32:18,504
[Ring]

718
00:32:20,306 --> 00:32:22,308
[Ring]

719
00:32:22,340 --> 00:32:24,110
Santaville inn.

720
00:32:38,457 --> 00:32:41,392
I'm not staring. I swear.

721
00:32:41,792 --> 00:32:44,130
Uh-huh.

722
00:32:44,163 --> 00:32:45,031
But I'm wondering...

723
00:32:45,064 --> 00:32:48,067
And I know this'll
sound like a line. Uh...

724
00:32:48,100 --> 00:32:49,501
But do you come here often?

725
00:32:49,535 --> 00:32:53,371
Yeah, why would that
sound like a line?

726
00:32:53,404 --> 00:32:55,174
I'm genuinely curious.

727
00:32:55,206 --> 00:32:57,342
You don't look like a local.

728
00:32:57,375 --> 00:32:59,545
Not for a long time.

729
00:32:59,578 --> 00:33:01,980
And you're not exactly
the santaville type yourself.

730
00:33:01,980 --> 00:33:06,485
I am staying here at the inn,
but I'm in from out of town

731
00:33:06,518 --> 00:33:08,320
Visiting an old college friend
and his wife.

732
00:33:08,354 --> 00:33:11,189
I was actually supposed to meet
here at 4:00, but, uh...

733
00:33:11,223 --> 00:33:14,293
Your friends wouldn't happen
to be Roger and della Wallace?

734
00:33:14,326 --> 00:33:15,461
How'd you know?

735
00:33:15,494 --> 00:33:18,196
I... i was supposed
to meet them, too.

736
00:33:18,230 --> 00:33:20,398
Wait a second.
Do you think they...

737
00:33:20,431 --> 00:33:24,335
Yeah. Yeah, we've been set up,
big time.

738
00:33:24,370 --> 00:33:26,038
Heh heh.
[Cellphone rings]

739
00:33:26,072 --> 00:33:28,574
Well, gee,
I wonder who that could be?

740
00:33:28,607 --> 00:33:31,177
- Ben, is that you?
- Hey, Roger.

741
00:33:31,209 --> 00:33:32,277
Yeah, I'm here.

742
00:33:32,311 --> 00:33:33,679
Sorry I can't come.

743
00:33:33,711 --> 00:33:34,513
Oh, no.

744
00:33:34,546 --> 00:33:35,614
Kids have fevers.

745
00:33:35,647 --> 00:33:36,615
Fever, huh?

746
00:33:36,648 --> 00:33:37,616
All 3 boys.

747
00:33:37,649 --> 00:33:38,717
All 3 boys.

748
00:33:38,749 --> 00:33:41,319
Wow. That's terrible. I'm sorry.

749
00:33:41,352 --> 00:33:42,820
Say hi to my friend.

750
00:33:42,853 --> 00:33:44,389
Really? What's her name?

751
00:33:44,422 --> 00:33:45,224
Holly Crosby.

752
00:33:45,256 --> 00:33:48,194
Holly Crosby.
That's a pretty name.

753
00:33:48,227 --> 00:33:49,661
What's she look like?

754
00:33:49,695 --> 00:33:50,461
Great.

755
00:33:50,495 --> 00:33:52,064
How good-looking?

756
00:33:52,098 --> 00:33:52,731
Exquisite.

757
00:33:52,763 --> 00:33:54,265
Wow, that good-lookin', huh?

758
00:33:54,300 --> 00:33:55,167
- Say hi.
- Ok, I will.

759
00:33:55,201 --> 00:33:58,537
Thanks, man.
I'll catch up with you later.

760
00:33:58,570 --> 00:33:59,770
Yeah, later, man.

761
00:33:59,805 --> 00:34:00,471
Bye.

762
00:34:00,505 --> 00:34:02,040
He wants me to introduce myself

763
00:34:02,040 --> 00:34:06,477
And explain his sons are sick.
You get the idea.

764
00:34:06,511 --> 00:34:07,579
Yeah. Della.

765
00:34:07,613 --> 00:34:09,081
Hi. I'm Ben Richards.

766
00:34:09,115 --> 00:34:11,450
You do not have to do this.

767
00:34:11,482 --> 00:34:12,351
Oh, yes, I do.

768
00:34:12,384 --> 00:34:16,187
It would mean so much
to Roger and della.

769
00:34:18,523 --> 00:34:19,757
See over there?

770
00:34:19,791 --> 00:34:21,459
Oh, yeah.

771
00:34:21,492 --> 00:34:22,693
This is incredible.

772
00:34:22,728 --> 00:34:26,132
I didn't think places
like this still existed.

773
00:34:26,165 --> 00:34:27,832
They are
an endangered species.

774
00:34:27,866 --> 00:34:31,336
And your dad put all this
together himself?

775
00:34:31,370 --> 00:34:32,638
Yeah, pretty much.

776
00:34:32,671 --> 00:34:35,574
I mean,
he was the creative force.

777
00:34:35,607 --> 00:34:36,507
But it was my mom

778
00:34:36,541 --> 00:34:39,310
Who had all the business sense
in the family.

779
00:34:39,345 --> 00:34:42,848
I mean, she knew how much he was
into the whole Santa thing,

780
00:34:42,880 --> 00:34:47,253
And... and this way
he could make all those
other kids really happy

781
00:34:47,286 --> 00:34:48,720
And still support his family.

782
00:34:48,754 --> 00:34:50,455
Wow. Heh. You must have had,

783
00:34:50,488 --> 00:34:53,359
Like, the most amazing
childhood on record.

784
00:34:53,391 --> 00:34:54,160
[Chuckles]

785
00:34:54,193 --> 00:34:56,827
I mean,
you grew up in santaville.

786
00:34:56,862 --> 00:35:01,532
Uh... heh.
It... it had its moments.

787
00:35:02,100 --> 00:35:03,702
You mind if I ask you

788
00:35:03,735 --> 00:35:09,508
How your dad affords to keep
this place open all year round?

789
00:35:10,476 --> 00:35:13,278
Um, he can't.

790
00:35:13,311 --> 00:35:14,480
Not anymore.

791
00:35:14,513 --> 00:35:16,714
Oh, yeah? What do you mean?

792
00:35:16,747 --> 00:35:18,617
Oh. Well, look around.

793
00:35:18,650 --> 00:35:20,885
I mean, all these
beautiful buildings,

794
00:35:20,919 --> 00:35:23,254
But there's no people.

795
00:35:23,289 --> 00:35:24,356
Times have changed.

796
00:35:24,389 --> 00:35:27,458
Nobody's interested in
a traditional Christmas anymore.

797
00:35:27,493 --> 00:35:30,729
So now he's
in a bit of a pickle.

798
00:35:30,761 --> 00:35:33,299
How bad is it?

799
00:35:33,331 --> 00:35:35,167
He could lose everything.

800
00:35:35,201 --> 00:35:38,337
Come on. This is
prime new england property,

801
00:35:38,369 --> 00:35:39,370
Charming little town.

802
00:35:39,405 --> 00:35:42,241
I mean, you know
how the world works.

803
00:35:42,274 --> 00:35:43,642
It's gotta be worth somethin'.

804
00:35:43,675 --> 00:35:46,944
Oh. [Scoffs]
Selling is not an option.

805
00:35:46,977 --> 00:35:48,747
Well, what about a loan then?

806
00:35:48,780 --> 00:35:52,184
He couldn't borrow enough
to buy a candy cane.

807
00:35:52,218 --> 00:35:56,554
In that case, it sounds to me
like you guys are in need

808
00:35:56,587 --> 00:35:59,590
Of the services
of a good financial advisor.

809
00:35:59,624 --> 00:36:02,160
Sure. I'll just Google one up.

810
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:04,530
Well, there's a rumor
goin' around

811
00:36:04,562 --> 00:36:06,732
That this new guy,
Ben Richards,

812
00:36:06,764 --> 00:36:08,867
Might know a thing or two.

813
00:36:08,899 --> 00:36:10,402
You? Seriously?

814
00:36:10,435 --> 00:36:12,803
I can't promise anything,
but...

815
00:36:12,837 --> 00:36:14,439
I might know some people.

816
00:36:14,473 --> 00:36:16,707
People? What...
What does that mean?

817
00:36:16,742 --> 00:36:19,911
Just means I can make
a couple of phone calls.

818
00:36:19,944 --> 00:36:20,945
If you'd like.

819
00:36:20,979 --> 00:36:21,980
Are you kidding?

820
00:36:22,012 --> 00:36:23,381
Yes. Um, please.

821
00:36:23,415 --> 00:36:26,352
Gosh, i... i am in
way over my head here.

822
00:36:26,384 --> 00:36:30,821
Anything you could do for...
I just... i would be so...

823
00:36:31,690 --> 00:36:32,858
Thank you.

824
00:36:32,890 --> 00:36:36,362
You're welcome, holly.

825
00:36:40,799 --> 00:36:42,868
Dad!

826
00:36:51,877 --> 00:36:53,379
[Creak]

827
00:36:53,412 --> 00:36:54,011
Oh.

828
00:36:54,044 --> 00:36:54,913
Sorry. I... i...

829
00:36:54,945 --> 00:36:55,881
No, that's ok.

830
00:36:55,914 --> 00:36:58,284
I was looking for my father.

831
00:36:58,317 --> 00:37:01,253
I think he's in the house.

832
00:37:01,287 --> 00:37:03,554
Is this yours?

833
00:37:03,589 --> 00:37:05,424
It's just a hobby.

834
00:37:05,457 --> 00:37:09,361
No. They're...
They're beautiful.

835
00:37:09,394 --> 00:37:10,095
Thank you.

836
00:37:10,128 --> 00:37:11,862
Does my father
know about this?

837
00:37:11,896 --> 00:37:14,865
- I would say probably.
- Probably?

838
00:37:14,899 --> 00:37:17,536
Well, I leave one
under his tree every year,

839
00:37:17,569 --> 00:37:20,004
But we've never actually
really talked about it.

840
00:37:20,038 --> 00:37:23,574
I have noticed he makes a point
never to come back here.

841
00:37:23,609 --> 00:37:27,512
Think he still wants
to believe in the magic.

842
00:37:33,485 --> 00:37:34,920
Have you ever considered
marketing these?

843
00:37:34,953 --> 00:37:40,392
I mean, you just don't find this
kind of craftsmanship anymore.

844
00:37:41,460 --> 00:37:45,397
Like I said, just a hobby.

845
00:37:46,063 --> 00:37:49,301
Well, you must
really like nutcrackers.

846
00:37:49,335 --> 00:37:53,070
Someone told me a story
about the ballet
a long time ago.

847
00:37:53,103 --> 00:37:55,673
Been hooked ever since.

848
00:37:56,408 --> 00:37:58,008
Clara, Fritz,

849
00:37:58,043 --> 00:38:00,946
Herr drosselmeyer.

850
00:38:06,652 --> 00:38:08,420
Peter...

851
00:38:10,488 --> 00:38:11,956
Hi.

852
00:38:13,057 --> 00:38:15,393
You make things.

853
00:38:15,426 --> 00:38:17,462
Yeah.

854
00:38:21,632 --> 00:38:23,701
You just left.

855
00:38:25,436 --> 00:38:27,606
I came back.

856
00:38:29,040 --> 00:38:31,477
Yeah.

857
00:38:36,046 --> 00:38:40,452
I... i really have to
go find my father.

858
00:38:40,486 --> 00:38:42,620
Can we talk later?

859
00:38:42,653 --> 00:38:44,823
Sure.

860
00:38:47,859 --> 00:38:50,561
So I'll just see you.

861
00:38:50,596 --> 00:38:52,931
Ok.

862
00:39:08,980 --> 00:39:13,084
So, Morgan, you've been
a good little girl all year?

863
00:39:13,117 --> 00:39:15,119
You've got a chimney?

864
00:39:15,153 --> 00:39:15,854
Good.

865
00:39:15,886 --> 00:39:17,723
You've got a list.

866
00:39:17,756 --> 00:39:18,756
Tiara.

867
00:39:18,789 --> 00:39:21,860
Ok, we might have
a little trouble with the pony,

868
00:39:21,893 --> 00:39:25,062
But a charm bracelet, yeah,
red scooter,

869
00:39:25,096 --> 00:39:28,033
Makeup set.

870
00:39:32,202 --> 00:39:34,039
Dad.

871
00:39:34,071 --> 00:39:35,172
Well?

872
00:39:35,205 --> 00:39:36,007
Well, what?

873
00:39:36,041 --> 00:39:37,576
Well, what's the plan
with corwell?

874
00:39:37,608 --> 00:39:41,079
Oh. There's no plan.
He couldn't help us.

875
00:39:41,111 --> 00:39:41,947
What do you mean?

876
00:39:41,980 --> 00:39:43,649
W... you're mortgaged
to the hilt, dad.

877
00:39:43,681 --> 00:39:46,116
The bank's in line
with everyone else.

878
00:39:46,151 --> 00:39:46,885
What did you expect?

879
00:39:46,918 --> 00:39:48,454
I... i expected
a little loyalty,

880
00:39:48,487 --> 00:39:50,889
Maybe a little faith
in an old friend.

881
00:39:50,922 --> 00:39:51,722
Doesn't work that way.

882
00:39:51,756 --> 00:39:53,525
Then what are
we gonna do about it?

883
00:39:53,559 --> 00:39:55,994
I met someone today,
a financial advisor.

884
00:39:56,027 --> 00:39:59,465
A financial advisor.
That's good. That's good. Yeah.

885
00:39:59,498 --> 00:40:01,066
He's gonna try to help us.

886
00:40:01,099 --> 00:40:02,400
Try? He's...
Wh-what does "try" mean?

887
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:05,670
I don't know, dad.
50 grand's a lot of money.

888
00:40:05,703 --> 00:40:06,637
I'm... I'm sorta wingin' it here.

889
00:40:06,672 --> 00:40:08,974
Well, we gotta figure out
somethin', holly.

890
00:40:09,006 --> 00:40:11,442
You have to stop this.
You have to!

891
00:40:11,477 --> 00:40:12,744
Yeah, I know, dad. I get it.

892
00:40:12,778 --> 00:40:15,481
You're a wonderful man,
and this is your life,

893
00:40:15,513 --> 00:40:18,717
And the clock is ticking,
but maybe if you hadn't lived

894
00:40:18,749 --> 00:40:21,619
In such a blissful
state of denial for so long...

895
00:40:21,653 --> 00:40:24,490
Do I look blissful to you?!
Is this blissful?!

896
00:40:24,523 --> 00:40:27,158
Holly, I'm trying
to save my home, our home,

897
00:40:27,191 --> 00:40:29,461
And I thought
you cared about that.

898
00:40:29,495 --> 00:40:30,796
I do care, dad, but...

899
00:40:30,828 --> 00:40:33,732
But see, that's the thing.
There is no buts, ever.

900
00:40:33,764 --> 00:40:35,534
You're either in, or you're out.

901
00:40:35,567 --> 00:40:36,867
That's the way it works.

902
00:40:36,901 --> 00:40:39,804
This is everything your mother
and I ever worked for,

903
00:40:39,837 --> 00:40:43,642
And if I lose santaville,
then I have nothing.

904
00:40:44,875 --> 00:40:46,777
Nothing.

905
00:40:49,780 --> 00:40:51,483
You have me!

906
00:40:54,019 --> 00:40:55,521
[Groans]

907
00:41:02,460 --> 00:41:03,994
Holly.

908
00:41:05,564 --> 00:41:06,230
Ben. Hi.

909
00:41:06,263 --> 00:41:08,198
I was just comin' to find you.

910
00:41:08,233 --> 00:41:11,837
You do know
it's December, right?

911
00:41:12,737 --> 00:41:14,071
What is it?

912
00:41:14,104 --> 00:41:15,072
I wanted to tell you
right away.

913
00:41:15,105 --> 00:41:17,575
I made those phone calls
I was tellin' you about.

914
00:41:17,608 --> 00:41:19,645
I don't know.
This never happens.

915
00:41:19,677 --> 00:41:20,579
What?

916
00:41:20,611 --> 00:41:22,514
I don't wanna
get your hopes up too much,

917
00:41:22,548 --> 00:41:25,283
But these people
are very interested.

918
00:41:25,315 --> 00:41:26,084
Seriously?

919
00:41:26,116 --> 00:41:26,884
It's incredible.

920
00:41:26,917 --> 00:41:28,753
They got great ideas,
very creative.

921
00:41:28,787 --> 00:41:29,521
Well, tell me.

922
00:41:29,555 --> 00:41:31,557
No, I don't wanna say
too much.

923
00:41:31,590 --> 00:41:34,225
It's very fluid,
and I don't wanna jinx it.

924
00:41:34,258 --> 00:41:36,161
We'll call 'em in the morning.

925
00:41:36,194 --> 00:41:37,062
Oh, come on, Ben.

926
00:41:37,095 --> 00:41:37,763
Not until I'm sure.

927
00:41:37,795 --> 00:41:39,229
Think of it like having to wait

928
00:41:39,264 --> 00:41:42,100
Until Christmas Eve
to open your presents.

929
00:41:42,133 --> 00:41:45,036
Wait. You open your presents
on Christmas Eve?

930
00:41:45,070 --> 00:41:46,104
Sure.

931
00:41:46,137 --> 00:41:47,138
What?

932
00:41:47,172 --> 00:41:49,840
No, it's just that Santa
comes on Christmas Eve.

933
00:41:49,874 --> 00:41:51,308
The presents
are for Christmas morning.

934
00:41:51,341 --> 00:41:53,278
Ok. I'll remember that
from now on,

935
00:41:53,310 --> 00:41:55,245
But the point
is I may have just found

936
00:41:55,280 --> 00:41:57,915
That Christmas miracle
you've been hopin' for.

937
00:41:57,948 --> 00:41:59,785
Thank you so much.

938
00:41:59,817 --> 00:42:02,520
Oh! This is gonna be great.

939
00:42:03,889 --> 00:42:06,592
Thank you, Ben.

940
00:42:28,046 --> 00:42:29,848
Covered bridge.

941
00:42:49,234 --> 00:42:50,201
Hey.

942
00:42:50,235 --> 00:42:52,170
Hi.

943
00:42:52,203 --> 00:42:53,639
I got your note.

944
00:42:53,672 --> 00:42:56,341
Great.

945
00:42:58,677 --> 00:43:00,245
My mom used to bring me here

946
00:43:00,278 --> 00:43:02,247
When things would get
a little too crazy.

947
00:43:02,280 --> 00:43:05,951
Sometimes we wouldn't even talk.
We'd just listen to the water.

948
00:43:05,983 --> 00:43:09,220
I'd be all geeked out
about something or other,

949
00:43:09,253 --> 00:43:13,724
And that sound
would be so relaxing.

950
00:43:13,758 --> 00:43:17,628
She told me stories, and...
And we'd laugh, and...

951
00:43:17,663 --> 00:43:22,167
Yeah, and then I'd just forget
what was even bothering me.

952
00:43:22,200 --> 00:43:24,402
She always knew just what to do.

953
00:43:24,434 --> 00:43:26,838
She sounds like
a great person.

954
00:43:26,871 --> 00:43:29,006
She was.

955
00:43:29,039 --> 00:43:32,610
Nick never talks about her.

956
00:43:33,344 --> 00:43:35,613
Ah, you noticed.

957
00:43:36,314 --> 00:43:39,349
None of my business.

958
00:43:45,190 --> 00:43:48,794
When I was little,
family was his whole life...

959
00:43:48,827 --> 00:43:50,395
Me and my mom.

960
00:43:50,427 --> 00:43:53,164
When she died, he changed.

961
00:43:53,198 --> 00:43:54,299
I was 12.

962
00:43:54,332 --> 00:43:57,669
It's like the only way
he could hang on

963
00:43:57,703 --> 00:44:00,971
Was to go all Santa
all the time.

964
00:44:01,005 --> 00:44:03,875
A heart big enough
to hold the whole world,

965
00:44:03,908 --> 00:44:10,314
But when it came
to his real family, me, well...

966
00:44:10,348 --> 00:44:12,249
So you left.

967
00:44:12,282 --> 00:44:14,652
Yep.

968
00:44:16,353 --> 00:44:20,759
That day in the toy shop,
why'd you disappear like that?

969
00:44:20,791 --> 00:44:22,393
My parents were in a hurry.

970
00:44:22,426 --> 00:44:26,331
We, uh, still had a long drive
ahead of us.

971
00:44:26,363 --> 00:44:27,398
Visiting relatives?

972
00:44:27,431 --> 00:44:29,034
Back to school.

973
00:44:29,066 --> 00:44:31,036
No, wait.
I-it was Christmas break.

974
00:44:31,068 --> 00:44:32,102
Everyone was out of school.

975
00:44:32,136 --> 00:44:35,340
Yeah, well, they kept
the dorms open just in case.

976
00:44:35,373 --> 00:44:36,573
In case of what?

977
00:44:36,606 --> 00:44:39,745
In case your parents wanted to
fly to Europe for the holidays

978
00:44:39,778 --> 00:44:42,347
And taking you along didn't
exactly fit into their plans.

979
00:44:42,380 --> 00:44:46,952
Your parents left you in
boarding school over Christmas?

980
00:44:46,984 --> 00:44:49,287
On the plus side, I got a lot
of extra studying done,

981
00:44:49,320 --> 00:44:53,191
Which meant I graduated early,
moved to college,

982
00:44:53,224 --> 00:44:54,325
Which really simplified

983
00:44:54,359 --> 00:44:57,295
Mom and dad's plans
for the world cruise.

984
00:44:57,328 --> 00:44:59,898
That must have been awful.

985
00:44:59,930 --> 00:45:02,700
No. It was...
It was normal to me.

986
00:45:02,700 --> 00:45:04,369
Mmm...

987
00:45:04,402 --> 00:45:06,037
Actually all worked out.

988
00:45:06,071 --> 00:45:09,074
I went to college
for, like, a decade,

989
00:45:09,107 --> 00:45:10,275
Got several degrees,

990
00:45:10,307 --> 00:45:15,113
And then dad tried to squeeze me
into his world of business.

991
00:45:15,145 --> 00:45:16,747
I rebelled, he cut me off,

992
00:45:16,782 --> 00:45:20,918
So I decided to do
some traveling of my own.

993
00:45:20,952 --> 00:45:24,322
I remembered a certain elf

994
00:45:24,354 --> 00:45:27,258
With a love of the ballet.

995
00:45:27,292 --> 00:45:28,794
Here I am.

996
00:45:28,827 --> 00:45:30,896
You came back here
because of me?

997
00:45:30,928 --> 00:45:34,900
That and Christmas
365 days a year.

998
00:45:34,933 --> 00:45:36,334
[Laughs]

999
00:45:36,367 --> 00:45:43,173
I would have traded places
with you in a heartbeat.

1000
00:45:44,342 --> 00:45:48,279
Believe me, it wasn't all
candy canes and sleigh rides.

1001
00:45:48,313 --> 00:45:50,080
Ah, it doesn't have to be,

1002
00:45:50,114 --> 00:45:53,418
As long as you have
someone who loves you

1003
00:45:53,451 --> 00:45:56,186
And wants you to be happy,

1004
00:45:56,220 --> 00:45:58,523
And that's
what you had here, holly.

1005
00:45:58,555 --> 00:46:01,326
It's what you still have here.

1006
00:46:01,359 --> 00:46:03,995
It's all I ever wanted.

1007
00:46:04,528 --> 00:46:07,465
[Cellphone rings]

1008
00:46:08,166 --> 00:46:10,468
[Ring]

1009
00:46:11,401 --> 00:46:12,003
[Ring]

1010
00:46:12,036 --> 00:46:15,372
I, uh... i better take this.

1011
00:46:15,405 --> 00:46:16,874
[Ring]

1012
00:46:19,243 --> 00:46:20,311
Hello.

1013
00:46:20,345 --> 00:46:21,411
Holly.

1014
00:46:21,446 --> 00:46:23,113
Ben, hi.

1015
00:46:29,486 --> 00:46:32,323
Tellin' you, holly,
I've never seen a deal
close this quickly.

1016
00:46:32,357 --> 00:46:37,428
I mean, those folks are
even willin' to pay off
all your father's bills,

1017
00:46:37,462 --> 00:46:38,363
Wipe the slate clean.

1018
00:46:38,396 --> 00:46:39,430
That's a lot of money.

1019
00:46:39,464 --> 00:46:42,934
Aw, 50 or 60 grand,
small change to these people.

1020
00:46:42,968 --> 00:46:45,003
Well, it's a fortune
around here.

1021
00:46:45,035 --> 00:46:46,337
What do they get out of it?

1022
00:46:46,371 --> 00:46:48,573
Well, the timing
couldn't have been more perfect.

1023
00:46:48,605 --> 00:46:49,807
These guys just quietly
closed a deal

1024
00:46:49,841 --> 00:46:53,177
For controlling interest in 2
ski resorts just north of here,

1025
00:46:53,210 --> 00:46:56,213
And the way they see it,
santaville's just another way

1026
00:46:56,246 --> 00:46:57,281
To draw more families
to the area.

1027
00:46:57,315 --> 00:47:00,150
You know, stop here
on the way up, on the way back.

1028
00:47:00,184 --> 00:47:02,286
You know, some kind of
package deal, maybe,

1029
00:47:02,320 --> 00:47:04,489
Free lift tickets
with every park pass,

1030
00:47:04,522 --> 00:47:05,290
Somethin' like that.

1031
00:47:05,323 --> 00:47:06,324
Yeah, that could...
That could work.

1032
00:47:06,356 --> 00:47:09,126
And after all, Roger's been
tellin' me for years

1033
00:47:09,160 --> 00:47:11,261
This little burg
is about to explode, so...

1034
00:47:11,296 --> 00:47:16,067
And anyway, point is your dad's
not hangin' in the wind anymore.

1035
00:47:16,100 --> 00:47:17,235
He's got partners now.

1036
00:47:17,267 --> 00:47:20,338
Oh, he won't let anyone
tell him how to run this place.

1037
00:47:20,371 --> 00:47:22,306
Oh, no, no, no.
Silent partners. Absolutely.

1038
00:47:22,340 --> 00:47:24,442
Don't worry.
Your dad's still the man.

1039
00:47:24,474 --> 00:47:29,881
[Sighs] It sounds perfect.
Thank you.

1040
00:47:30,448 --> 00:47:32,217
Think he'll go for it?

1041
00:47:32,249 --> 00:47:35,386
How could he say no?

1042
00:47:35,420 --> 00:47:38,255
No. I've never needed anyone's
help to run this place

1043
00:47:38,288 --> 00:47:42,592
Besides holly and her mother,
and I don't intend to start now.

1044
00:47:42,627 --> 00:47:44,261
It's a good deal, Mr. Crosby.

1045
00:47:44,294 --> 00:47:47,197
It's better than you'll find
anyplace else.

1046
00:47:47,231 --> 00:47:48,232
I need money, not partners.

1047
00:47:48,265 --> 00:47:50,600
Silent partners, dad.
You'd still be in charge.

1048
00:47:50,635 --> 00:47:54,372
Oh, and how would these silent
partners get their money back?

1049
00:47:54,405 --> 00:47:56,306
They do want
their money back, right?

1050
00:47:56,340 --> 00:47:59,410
Aw, eventually, of course,
and with fair market interest,

1051
00:47:59,444 --> 00:48:02,279
But not until
you're back on your feet.

1052
00:48:02,312 --> 00:48:07,351
But in the meantime,
they'd own a piece of my home.

1053
00:48:07,385 --> 00:48:08,286
Technically that's true.

1054
00:48:08,318 --> 00:48:09,319
But it would better
than losing your home,

1055
00:48:09,353 --> 00:48:12,489
Which is what'll happen
if you don't do this soon.

1056
00:48:12,522 --> 00:48:13,523
Not interested.

1057
00:48:13,557 --> 00:48:14,625
At least read it.

1058
00:48:14,658 --> 00:48:16,962
I don't have to read it.
I know exactly what it says.

1059
00:48:16,994 --> 00:48:19,397
It's a lot of legal words
that boils down to one thing.

1060
00:48:19,430 --> 00:48:23,068
You gave up
on santaville years ago,
and you're doin' it again.

1061
00:48:23,100 --> 00:48:25,669
Gave up?
Dad, I went to college.

1062
00:48:25,703 --> 00:48:27,371
I got a job, a career.

1063
00:48:27,405 --> 00:48:29,440
Right, and you were
supposed to come back here

1064
00:48:29,474 --> 00:48:32,944
And be my number one elf
and help me run this place.

1065
00:48:32,978 --> 00:48:36,380
I mean, that... that's all
I ever really was to you,

1066
00:48:36,414 --> 00:48:37,247
Just some silly mascot

1067
00:48:37,281 --> 00:48:41,052
Dressed up in a costume
all these years.

1068
00:48:41,086 --> 00:48:43,220
You know better than that.

1069
00:48:43,253 --> 00:48:44,956
How would I know?

1070
00:48:44,990 --> 00:48:46,356
When did you ever tell me?

1071
00:48:46,390 --> 00:48:52,197
Since mom died,
when did you once say to me...

1072
00:48:59,104 --> 00:49:00,705
Good day, Ben.

1073
00:49:12,417 --> 00:49:16,486
You are a damn fool,
Nick Crosby.

1074
00:49:18,488 --> 00:49:20,025
Shut up.

1075
00:49:35,640 --> 00:49:38,743
[Vehicle approaching]

1076
00:49:47,085 --> 00:49:49,087
Heard you were leaving.

1077
00:49:49,620 --> 00:49:51,689
Without saying good-bye?

1078
00:49:52,322 --> 00:49:53,323
Good-bye, Peter.

1079
00:49:53,357 --> 00:49:55,325
You know, sometimes people

1080
00:49:55,359 --> 00:49:58,129
Don't know how
to say what they feel.

1081
00:49:58,163 --> 00:50:00,397
The words just won't come out.

1082
00:50:00,430 --> 00:50:03,000
Talk about everything
except what...

1083
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:06,436
Really matters to him the most.

1084
00:50:08,073 --> 00:50:09,207
Yeah.

1085
00:50:09,239 --> 00:50:10,075
Yeah, it's funny.

1086
00:50:10,107 --> 00:50:12,310
I always thought
I was a great listener.

1087
00:50:12,343 --> 00:50:16,180
I mean, I got 30 years
experience, so I ought to be.

1088
00:50:16,213 --> 00:50:20,051
Turns out I'm great at listenin'
to everyone but you,

1089
00:50:20,085 --> 00:50:22,387
And I'm really sorry, holly,

1090
00:50:22,419 --> 00:50:23,653
And I wanna fix that.

1091
00:50:23,688 --> 00:50:27,357
I just wanted you
to be my dad.

1092
00:50:27,657 --> 00:50:30,360
That's all
I ever wanted to be.

1093
00:50:30,395 --> 00:50:32,097
But you were always so busy

1094
00:50:32,130 --> 00:50:35,399
Being jolly and merry
for everybody else,

1095
00:50:35,432 --> 00:50:36,567
Always Santa.

1096
00:50:36,601 --> 00:50:39,670
Well, maybe that's 'cause
it's easier to live in a world

1097
00:50:39,704 --> 00:50:43,308
Where wishes do come true, ok,
where everybody is happy,

1098
00:50:43,340 --> 00:50:44,675
Where nobody ever leaves me.

1099
00:50:44,709 --> 00:50:47,245
I couldn't live
in that world, dad,

1100
00:50:47,277 --> 00:50:50,815
Pretending like the past
never happened.

1101
00:50:50,847 --> 00:50:53,517
I still miss her all the time.

1102
00:50:53,551 --> 00:50:55,385
So do i. So do I, honey.

1103
00:50:55,419 --> 00:50:59,356
But you never talk about her.
It's like she was never here.

1104
00:50:59,389 --> 00:51:01,425
She was here.

1105
00:51:03,060 --> 00:51:05,796
Some days, I think she still is,

1106
00:51:05,829 --> 00:51:08,433
Because I can see her.

1107
00:51:08,798 --> 00:51:12,303
I can see her in your eyes,
your smile.

1108
00:51:12,336 --> 00:51:16,506
And when you laugh,
I can hear her.

1109
00:51:17,142 --> 00:51:21,345
She's been here a lot
these last few days.

1110
00:51:23,248 --> 00:51:25,183
Really?

1111
00:51:27,185 --> 00:51:28,153
Yeah.

1112
00:51:28,186 --> 00:51:31,788
It's a wonderful thing
havin' you come back home.

1113
00:51:32,657 --> 00:51:35,325
I miss you, too, dad,

1114
00:51:35,360 --> 00:51:37,494
So much.

1115
00:51:42,532 --> 00:51:46,304
Please don't leave,
honey, not yet.

1116
00:52:01,851 --> 00:52:02,887
Mmm, scones.

1117
00:52:02,919 --> 00:52:05,623
You know, i... i thought about
what you said last night

1118
00:52:05,655 --> 00:52:08,493
About how I never
talked about your mother.

1119
00:52:08,526 --> 00:52:10,227
Dad, you don't have to.

1120
00:52:10,261 --> 00:52:11,295
No, no, no. You're right.

1121
00:52:11,328 --> 00:52:14,664
You're right. I haven't,
and it's very selfish of me,

1122
00:52:14,699 --> 00:52:17,567
Because she was
an amazing woman.

1123
00:52:18,369 --> 00:52:19,469
I remember.

1124
00:52:19,504 --> 00:52:21,939
But there's a lot
you don't remember,

1125
00:52:21,971 --> 00:52:26,311
And I want you to.
Important things.

1126
00:52:26,343 --> 00:52:28,213
So...

1127
00:52:28,246 --> 00:52:32,817
I figured it was about time
we opened this up.

1128
00:52:32,849 --> 00:52:34,851
Go ahead.

1129
00:52:41,659 --> 00:52:43,694
Dad...

1130
00:52:46,264 --> 00:52:49,667
In here is every letter,
card, and note

1131
00:52:49,700 --> 00:52:51,635
Your mom ever sent to me.

1132
00:52:51,669 --> 00:52:56,406
I mean, a lot of the notes
are silly.

1133
00:52:56,441 --> 00:52:57,308
I saved everything.

1134
00:52:57,342 --> 00:52:59,777
"I'll always love you,"
and stuff that...

1135
00:52:59,810 --> 00:53:03,180
She'd sneak in my pants
in the morning, and...

1136
00:53:03,180 --> 00:53:05,715
Then I'd find it later.

1137
00:53:05,750 --> 00:53:07,651
Uh, she was funny.

1138
00:53:07,685 --> 00:53:12,356
Oh, and this is the first
Christmas card we ever made you.

1139
00:53:12,389 --> 00:53:13,457
Remember?

1140
00:53:13,491 --> 00:53:15,392
Ah.

1141
00:53:15,426 --> 00:53:17,294
Oh, and there's pictures.

1142
00:53:17,327 --> 00:53:19,230
Remember when
you won the spelling bee?

1143
00:53:19,264 --> 00:53:23,501
You were in the third grade, and
you beat the sixth graders. Huh?

1144
00:53:23,533 --> 00:53:28,338
And this is your mom and I's
first date.

1145
00:53:28,373 --> 00:53:29,606
Fancy.

1146
00:53:29,639 --> 00:53:34,312
And this is from our honeymoon,
when we went to wisconson dales.

1147
00:53:34,344 --> 00:53:39,516
Lot of people go to Vegas, but
not good enough for your mom.

1148
00:53:39,750 --> 00:53:42,387
Oh, and this.

1149
00:53:43,388 --> 00:53:46,956
The night I asked her
to marry me...

1150
00:53:47,725 --> 00:53:50,361
I gave her this ring.

1151
00:53:50,395 --> 00:53:55,333
And our wedding rings
are in here, too.

1152
00:53:55,366 --> 00:53:57,534
And I want you to have this,

1153
00:53:57,567 --> 00:54:00,537
And maybe one day...

1154
00:54:00,771 --> 00:54:03,240
You'll need 'em.

1155
00:54:07,378 --> 00:54:09,614
And then there's this.

1156
00:54:16,487 --> 00:54:17,421
Mistletoe?

1157
00:54:17,454 --> 00:54:21,359
This is from the first night
I met your mom.

1158
00:54:21,391 --> 00:54:24,829
My friends were havin' a party,
and I almost didn't go,

1159
00:54:24,862 --> 00:54:27,432
But I did,
and I walked in the door,

1160
00:54:27,464 --> 00:54:33,270
And I saw your mom
standing in the moonlight
under the mistletoe.

1161
00:54:34,471 --> 00:54:37,408
Moonlight and mistletoe.

1162
00:54:37,442 --> 00:54:38,675
Yeah.

1163
00:54:38,708 --> 00:54:41,779
And so, I don't know
what got into me,

1164
00:54:41,812 --> 00:54:44,482
But I went right up
and kissed her.

1165
00:54:44,514 --> 00:54:45,916
And it could've gone either way,

1166
00:54:45,950 --> 00:54:50,355
'Cause your mom was
very beautiful, and I was, uh...

1167
00:54:50,388 --> 00:54:51,254
Me...

1168
00:54:51,288 --> 00:54:55,759
But as luck would have it,
it went my way,

1169
00:54:55,793 --> 00:54:59,529
And about a year later,
you were born.

1170
00:55:00,129 --> 00:55:02,433
That must have been some kiss.

1171
00:55:02,467 --> 00:55:03,300
I think she thought so.

1172
00:55:03,300 --> 00:55:07,805
And that's why you never
forget to hang the mistletoe.

1173
00:55:07,838 --> 00:55:10,708
Yeah. Well, there was
a lot of Christmas magic

1174
00:55:10,740 --> 00:55:12,476
In the air that night for me.

1175
00:55:12,509 --> 00:55:16,012
We all need a little
Christmas magic once in a while.

1176
00:55:16,046 --> 00:55:19,350
And if the mistletoe helps,
I figure, "why not?"

1177
00:55:19,384 --> 00:55:22,952
You might need some
one day, too, so...

1178
00:55:22,987 --> 00:55:25,055
But that's me. I'm just...

1179
00:55:25,088 --> 00:55:28,559
Probably just
a romantic old fool.

1180
00:55:30,727 --> 00:55:33,398
Anyway, I want you to...

1181
00:55:33,431 --> 00:55:34,699
Take care of her.

1182
00:55:34,731 --> 00:55:37,066
I will.

1183
00:55:37,101 --> 00:55:38,668
And you're not old. Heh.

1184
00:55:38,702 --> 00:55:41,771
I know. And I was thinkin'
about that other thing,

1185
00:55:41,805 --> 00:55:46,043
About the contract, and if
you think it's a good thing,

1186
00:55:46,075 --> 00:55:47,577
I'll sign it.

1187
00:55:47,612 --> 00:55:49,046
You mean it?

1188
00:55:49,078 --> 00:55:49,947
Yeah.

1189
00:55:49,980 --> 00:55:51,482
You're very smart, holly.

1190
00:55:51,516 --> 00:55:52,383
You're like your mom.

1191
00:55:52,417 --> 00:55:55,819
And it's time
I started listening to you.

1192
00:55:55,853 --> 00:55:57,888
You won't regret it, dad.

1193
00:55:57,922 --> 00:55:59,123
I know. I know.

1194
00:55:59,155 --> 00:56:03,360
And I got Earl lookin' at all
the legal mumbo jumbo right now.

1195
00:56:03,360 --> 00:56:05,662
Everything's gonna be ok.
I promise.

1196
00:56:05,696 --> 00:56:07,565
I know, holly.

1197
00:56:12,035 --> 00:56:13,537
I know.

1198
00:56:22,980 --> 00:56:24,449
There you go.

1199
00:56:24,482 --> 00:56:26,015
Thanks, Ginny.

1200
00:56:33,491 --> 00:56:35,625
[Sighs]

1201
00:56:45,035 --> 00:56:46,770
[Door opens, bell rings]

1202
00:56:46,803 --> 00:56:50,074
Decide to stay?

1203
00:56:50,107 --> 00:56:52,510
Yeah.

1204
00:56:52,809 --> 00:56:54,445
I'm glad.

1205
00:56:56,013 --> 00:56:57,482
I, uh, noticed

1206
00:56:57,515 --> 00:57:00,685
That you've been working
in here all morning,

1207
00:57:00,717 --> 00:57:04,522
And I thought
you might like hot coffee.

1208
00:57:04,555 --> 00:57:05,556
[Toy train whistle blows]

1209
00:57:05,589 --> 00:57:08,592
Oh. You read my mind.

1210
00:57:13,029 --> 00:57:14,598
I wanted to thank you

1211
00:57:14,631 --> 00:57:16,466
For being there last night.

1212
00:57:16,501 --> 00:57:18,002
I didn't do anything.

1213
00:57:18,034 --> 00:57:22,205
No, you have a way of
simplifying the truth.

1214
00:57:22,239 --> 00:57:24,708
What you said really helped.

1215
00:57:24,742 --> 00:57:28,845
For the first time in years,
dad and I actually talked.

1216
00:57:28,878 --> 00:57:32,449
He even agreed
to sign the contract.

1217
00:57:34,051 --> 00:57:35,720
So everything works out.

1218
00:57:35,752 --> 00:57:38,222
He gets to keep santaville,
and, uh...

1219
00:57:38,254 --> 00:57:41,758
You get to go back to the city.

1220
00:57:42,859 --> 00:57:45,229
Yeah.

1221
00:57:46,230 --> 00:57:49,567
I was planning on taking
the sleigh out tonight.

1222
00:57:49,600 --> 00:57:52,469
Why don't you come with me.

1223
00:57:52,670 --> 00:57:55,939
Uh, I'd like to,
but I'm meeting Ben.

1224
00:57:55,973 --> 00:58:00,010
He has to get the contract
to his people right away.

1225
00:58:00,044 --> 00:58:03,212
Mmm.
Maybe I should get people.

1226
00:58:03,247 --> 00:58:05,248
Makes you sound more important.

1227
00:58:05,282 --> 00:58:08,519
The investors, ok?

1228
00:58:09,319 --> 00:58:10,787
What's the rush?

1229
00:58:10,821 --> 00:58:12,289
They need to get
this deal together

1230
00:58:12,322 --> 00:58:13,323
Before the end
of the quarter,

1231
00:58:13,357 --> 00:58:15,826
Or else their tax liability
on the money doubles.

1232
00:58:15,860 --> 00:58:17,260
And we can't have that.

1233
00:58:17,294 --> 00:58:20,531
You really
don't like business, do you?

1234
00:58:20,565 --> 00:58:21,732
Been there.

1235
00:58:21,765 --> 00:58:23,266
[Toy train whistle blows]

1236
00:58:23,300 --> 00:58:26,269
I prefer sleigh rides.

1237
00:58:28,238 --> 00:58:30,507
Maybe another time.

1238
00:58:31,308 --> 00:58:32,208
Sure.

1239
00:58:32,242 --> 00:58:34,612
I'm not goin' anywhere.

1240
00:58:56,100 --> 00:58:58,135
Ok, now where does this go?

1241
00:58:58,168 --> 00:59:00,870
Um, on the top, Earl...

1242
00:59:00,904 --> 00:59:03,073
- Oh.
- Where it always goes...

1243
00:59:03,107 --> 00:59:03,540
Every year. Yeah. Yeah.

1244
00:59:03,540 --> 00:59:07,711
Try not to swallow
this one whole, Nick Crosby.

1245
00:59:07,745 --> 00:59:09,046
Ooh. Pie.

1246
00:59:09,079 --> 00:59:11,280
You act like I'm made of pies.

1247
00:59:11,315 --> 00:59:13,283
Well, see, that's our secret.

1248
00:59:13,316 --> 00:59:16,185
You make the pies,
and I eat the pies.

1249
00:59:16,219 --> 00:59:18,055
- [Scoffs]
- It's like words and music.

1250
00:59:18,087 --> 00:59:20,591
We belong together,
you know,

1251
00:59:20,625 --> 00:59:22,593
Like hot and toddy.

1252
00:59:22,627 --> 00:59:28,232
Only Santa could get away with
a line like that. Mmm.

1253
00:59:28,264 --> 00:59:29,966
Wow. Look at you.

1254
00:59:29,999 --> 00:59:32,001
You look great, honey.

1255
00:59:32,035 --> 00:59:33,269
Thank you.

1256
00:59:33,303 --> 00:59:34,371
Somebody's got a hot date.

1257
00:59:34,403 --> 00:59:37,608
No, it's not a date.
I'm just meeting Ben for dinner

1258
00:59:37,642 --> 00:59:39,343
To look over the paperwork.

1259
00:59:39,375 --> 00:59:44,013
Um, speaking of which, Earl,
do you have the contract?

1260
00:59:44,047 --> 00:59:46,250
Uh, yeah.

1261
00:59:46,283 --> 00:59:46,950
Yeah.

1262
00:59:46,983 --> 00:59:47,852
Anything I should know about?

1263
00:59:47,884 --> 00:59:52,857
Um, n-no, it's all
pretty standard stuff.

1264
00:59:52,889 --> 00:59:54,625
I-it seems fine to me.

1265
00:59:54,659 --> 00:59:57,094
Great. Dad, do you have a pen?

1266
00:59:57,127 --> 00:59:59,328
Mm-hmm. Course I have a pen.

1267
00:59:59,363 --> 01:00:01,231
Heh. [Stammers]

1268
01:00:01,265 --> 01:00:02,633
I'll go get one.

1269
01:00:02,667 --> 01:00:03,600
Ok, you get it.

1270
01:00:03,600 --> 01:00:07,370
Usually have a pen.

1271
01:00:09,038 --> 01:00:11,976
Wow. I'm impressed.

1272
01:00:12,009 --> 01:00:14,744
I thought your dad
threw in the towel.

1273
01:00:14,778 --> 01:00:17,146
Christmas is a time
for miracles.

1274
01:00:17,181 --> 01:00:20,083
Heh. I'm gonna remember that
from now on.

1275
01:00:20,117 --> 01:00:22,385
I can't thank you enough, Ben.

1276
01:00:22,419 --> 01:00:25,355
I mean, I feel like
this enormous weight

1277
01:00:25,388 --> 01:00:28,192
Has been lifted
